<HEADLINE> African Countries to Cooperate on Congo Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The African countries involved in
the civil conflict in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC)
Friday agreed to create an atmosphere of trust and commitment
among themselves so that the Lusaka peace agreement which was
signed last year could hold.
</P>
<P>
Briefing reporters after a one-day summit on the DRC conflict
held in Zimbabwe's prime resort town of Victoria Falls, Mozambican
President Joaquin Chissano who chaired the meeting said all the
four external forces that were represented agreed to meet
regularly to discuss the cease-fire issue.
</P>
<P>
The summit was also attended by South African President Thabo
Mbeki, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, Namibian President Sam
Nujoma, Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and Rwandan Foreign
Minister Andrei Bumaya.
</P>
<P>
The summit was meant to find ways of reducing the escalating
hostilities in the DRC and bringing trust and goodwill among the
six countries involved in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Angolan President Eduardo dos Santos and Rwanda's new President
 Paul Kagame failed to attend the summit.
</P>
<P>
Chissano said, "All the belligerents who were represented here
are keen to see the peace keeping force which will be sent by the
U.N. carry out its duties so that the Lusaka agreement will be as
successful as possible."
</P>
<P>
He said, "So it is now up to the United Nations to put all the
 logistics for the deployment of the peace keeping force because
as you can see, there is a political will on the part of the
leaders, whose forces are in the DRC."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council decided on February 24 to send 500
U.N. military observers to the DRC to monitor implementation of
the Lusaka ceasefire agreement, along with 5,000 troops to protect
them.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia have troops fighting alongside the
DRC army against those from Rwanda and Uganda who are supporting
rebels trying to topple the DRC President Laurent Kabila. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
