<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Willing to Develop Ties with Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammad
Said Al-Sahaf on Saturday received a letter from his United Arab
Emirates (UAE) counterpart Sheikh Hamdan Bin Zayed Al-Nehyan on
developing bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The letter stressed the importance of developing relations
between the two Gulf countries and touched upon ways to promote
them, reported the official INA news agency.
</P>
<P>
That UAE and Iraq develop relations conforms to the interests of
the two peoples as well as the Arab world, said the letter.
</P>
<P>
The letter, submitted by Ahmed Abdullah Ben Saeed, UAE charge
d'affaires In Iraq, came after the UAE reopened its embassy in the
Iraqi capital Baghdad on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The UAE charge d'affaires has stated the reopening of embassy in
Iraq is "a beginning of good and enhanced relations between the two
brotherly countries to serve their joint interests."
</P>
<P>
Iraq is also expected to reopen its consulate in Dubai, the
commercial center of the UAE, in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
The UAE severed its relations with Iraq after the latter invaded
Kuwait in 1990, and took part in the U.S.-led multinational
coalition that drove the Iraqi troops out of Kuwait in the 1991
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
However, bilateral relations, especially trade ties, have been
improving steadily in recent years. Trade volume between the two
countries, within the framework of the U.N. oil-for-food program,
has reached 400 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. humanitarian deal, launched in December 1996,
Iraq is allowed to export a limited amount of crude to finance
imports of food, medicine and other humanitarian goods.
</P>
<P>
Three of the six Gulf Cooperation Council member states--
Bahrain, Oman and Qatar--had renewed diplomatic ties with Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
