<HEADLINE> Saudi King Meets UAE Official on Boosting Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Saudi King Fahd met on
Saturday with visiting Abu Dhabi's Crown Prince Sheikh Khalifa Bin
Zayed al-Nahyan on ways of bolstering ties between the two Gulf
Arab nations.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, held in the western Saudi city of Jeddah, also
dealt with a wide-range Arab, Islamic and international issues, the
Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Before King Fahd, Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz had
already discussed similar issues with Sheikh Khalifa, who is also
Deputy Supreme Commander of the Armed Forces of the United Arab
Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
Gulf diplomatic sources said the dispute between UAE and Iran
over three Gulf islands and the Gulf Arab efforts to achieve a
peaceful solution dominated the meeting of Abdullah and Sheikh
Khalifa.
</P>
<P>
Both the UAE and Iran claimed sovereignty over the isles of Abu
Mussa and Greater and Lesser Tunbs, located in the mouth of the
strategic Strait of Hormuz. The islands are now controlled by Iran.
</P>
<P>
Since early last year, Abu Dhabi has been worried the increasing
warming-up of relations between some of its Gulf Arab neighbors and
Iran might undermine their support to the UAE over the territorial
dispute.
</P>
<P>
But foreign Ministers of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC)
formed last July a tripartite committee to devise a mechanism to
deal with the issue.
</P>
<P>
The ad hoc committee comprises foreign ministers of Oman, Qatar
and Saudi Arabia, three member states of the GCC. Bahrain, Kuwait
and the UAE are the other three members of the regional alliance.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Khalifa arrived in Saudi Arabia earlier Saturday. His
visit came one week ahead of the consultative meeting of the GCC
leaders, due in Oman on April 29.
</P>
<P>
The UAE-Iranian dispute is again likely to be reviewed at the
GCC bi-annual summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
