<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Spends Over 1 Billion Dollars for Food Subsidy Each Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Egypt spends more than 4 billion
Egyptian pounds (1.16 billion U.S. dollars) each year on
subsidizing basic foodstuffs, Minister of Supply and Internal Trade
Hassan Ali Khedr said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Up to 2.8 billion pounds (811.59 million dollars) are spent in
subsidizing bread, 655 million pounds (189.86 million dollars) for
sugar, and 634 million pounds (138.77 million dollars) for cooking
oil, Khedr said after a cabinet meeting chaired by President Hosni
Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
The subsidies should result in annual savings per household of
237.5 pounds (68.81 dollars) for bread, 76.3 pounds (22.12 dollars)
for sugar, and 73.9 (21.42 dollars) for oil, he added.
</P>
<P>
The per capita gross domestic product in Egypt is estimated to
stand at 4,100 pounds (1,200 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The cabinet meeting was devoted to finding ways to bring down
prices, and focused particularly on expanding wholesale business
and encouraging competition.
</P>
<P>
British Sainsbury's chain store has already sharpened price
competition by bringing in basic foodstuffs at half price.
Sainsbury was the first foreign supermarket chain to invest in
Egypt with stores opening in the Cairo area in the last few months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
