<HEADLINE> Arafat in Cairo for Talks with Mubarak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
arrived in Cairo Saturday evening, in the wake of his talks with U.
S. President Bill Clinton in Washington, for talks with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said earlier that he would
meet with Arafat later Saturday to discuss the outcome of Arafat's
talks Thursday with Clinton and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Arafat will brief Mubarak on his visit in Washington
and the U.S. promise to directly involve itself in the upcoming
peace negotiations between the Palestinians and Israel, Moussa
said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat discussed with Clinton and Albright in separate meetings
ways of accelerating the Palestinian-Israeli talks to meet a May
deadline for a framework agreement and a September target for a
final peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian and Israeli negotiators will begin talks in Eilat in
southern Israel after the Israeli Passover holiday, which ends on
April 26, to continue talks on the most difficult issues including
Jerusalem, refugees, Jewish settlement, water and borders.
</P>
<P>
Arafat frequently visits Egypt to discuss the peace march with
Mubarak. As president of the first Arab country to make peace with
Israel, Mubarak plays a mediatory role between the two sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat to Brief Mubarak on His Talks in Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Leader Yasser Arafat
will brief Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak Sunday on the outcome
of his recent talks in the United States, Egyptian Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told reporters that Arafat will arrive in Cairo Saturday
evening from Washington, and that he will confer with the
Palestinian leader later in the day on the latest developments of
the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat held separate talks with U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and President Bill Clinton Thursday on ways of
accelerating the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations to meet a May
deadline for a treaty framework and a September target for a final
peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Palestinian Ambassador to Egypt Zohdi al Qedra told
Egypt's Middle East News Agency that Arafat will keep Mubarak
posted on the U.S. promise to directly involve in the upcoming
talks between the Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The talks on a treaty framework are to begin after the Jewish
Passover holiday, which ends April 26. Palestinian and Israeli
negotiators will meet in Eilat in southern Israel for two weeks to
discuss the most thorny issues, including Jerusalem, refugees,
Jewish settlements and borders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
