<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Satisfied with Current Oil Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Oil Minister Sheikh
Saud Nasser Al-Sabah on Saturday voiced satisfaction with the
current crude prices, which he said could meet the needs to cover
kuwait's state budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from a meeting with the Parliament's Foreign Affairs
Committee, Sheikh Saud said the mechanism agreed at the latest
meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC)
would prevent oil price fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
"Now, we are not fearing a decline in prices... and crude prices
are stable and fair," Sheikh Saud told the press.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting in Vienna at the end of March, OPEC oil
ministers decided to raise their daily output by 1.7 million
barrels in order to cool off the global market, in which prices
surged to a nine-year high of over 30 U.S. dollars per barrel early
March.
</P>
<P>
The ministers designed to maintain crude prices within a range
of 22-28 dollars a barrel, saying OPEC members would raise or cut
production by 500,000 barrels per day if a 20-day average for a
basket of seven reference crudes strays outside the price range.
</P>
<P>
The 20-day average for the reference basket stood above 23
dollars per barrel last week.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's state budget for the fiscal year 2000/2001 starting on
July 1 was put at 4.635 billion Kuwaiti dinars (15.295 billion
dollars) with a deficit of 1.767 billion dinars (5.831 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
As the Kuwaiti government has calculated its oil revenues on a
conservative basis of 13 dollars per barrel, the deficit in the new
budget is likely to be killed if the price for Kuwait's crude could
stay at its current level of about 22 dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
