<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Approves Russia's New Military Doctrine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian President-Elect Vladimir
Putin approved the country's new military doctrine Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Putin's decree, which endorses the doctrine and takes effect
from its moment of publication, simultaneously rescinds a decree
by former President Boris Yeltsin to approve the previous doctrine.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Security Council, the top national security agency,
approved the final text of the new doctrine Friday.
</P>
<P>
At a council meeting in the Kremlin, Security Council
secretary Sergei Ivanov stressed the doctrine is defensive and its
main purposes are deterrence and the preservation of peace.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, it firmly advocates Russia's interests in
the military sphere, he said, and "the text of the military
doctrine meets Russia's national interests."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Security Council approved a draft of the new
military doctrine on February 4, which incorporates changes over
the past few years in the North Caucasus regions and in NATO
policies.
</P>
<P>
The council gave all of the key state organizations and
departments two months to finalize the draft military doctrine,
after which the president will sign a decree introducing the new
doctrine.
</P>
<P>
Russian President-Elect Vladimir Putin said the revision of
the old military doctrine was prompted by changes in Russia and
around the world in general.
</P>
<P>
Russia cannot "remain indifferent" to these changes, Putin
said, citing new threats that require new avenues of military
development.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Moscow "cannot help noticing changes in the
strategy of NATO," which in fact has become capable of making
decisions without U.N. sanction, Putin said. "We must react
appropriately" to all these changes in order to avoid "running
into surprises," he said.
</P>
<P>
The new doctrine stresses nuke deterrence. Under it, Russia
can use nuclear weapons only in case of an aggression against
itself or its allies and only when it is impossible to prevent by
conventional means the liquidation of Russia as a subject of
international relations.
</P>
<P>
The previous Russian military doctrine, which was approved on
November 2, 1993, did not announce a possibility of using nuclear
armaments so distinctly and firmly. It just outlined conditions
under which nuclear arms shall not be used. Those conditions
remain valid under the new doctrine.
</P>
<P>
Russia promises not to use nuclear arms against signatory
states to the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty of July 1, 1968 and
the states that don't have nuclear weapons, with the exception of
two circumstances: -- An armed attack at Russia, its territory,
Armed Forces and other troops or its allies by a country, which
has a union agreement with a nuclear power; -- Joint moves of such
a country and a nuclear power to invade or to make an armed attack
at Russia, its territory, Armed Forces and other troops or its
allies or to support such actions.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Strategic Nuclear Forces is made up of three
branches -- the Strategic Missile Troops, the Naval Strategic
Forces and the Strategic Aviation Forces.
</P>
<P>
The Strategic Missile Troops, equipped with silo and mobile
launchers, are a key component of the nuclear triad. They have 756
launchers with 3,385 nuclear warheads.
</P>
<P>
The Naval Strategic Nuclear Forces are composed of 26
strategic nuclear-powered submarines, including six submarine
missile-carrying cruisers of the Typhoon class, seven of the
Dolphin class and 13 of the Kamar (Squid) class. If fully loaded,
these nuclear-powered submarines can carry up to 440 ballistic
missiles with more than 2,000 warheads.
</P>
<P>
The Strategic Aviation has about 100 strategic assault
aircraft of the Tu-160, Tu-95MS and Tu-22MZ class, capable of
carrying more than 800 nuclear warheads.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of the military doctrine and the concept of
national security, as well as the ratification of START II and the
Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty by the parliament after
Putin's election as head of state, implies that Russia is more
actively searching for ways of achieving national security and
global strategic stability.
</P>
<P>
The approval of the two important treaties and the new
military doctrine are also seen as Putin's victories in domestic
and foreign policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prudential Closes To Bottom In Pension Table </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Prudential, Britain's biggest
insurer, plunged close to the bottom of the performance league
tables in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Its massive 2.6 billion pound fund is ranked 64th out of 67
funds, according to the latest industry figures from the Combined
Actuarial Performance Survey.
</P>
<P>
City observers believe the result is a huge embarrassment to
the Prudential, though it is not alone among big names in having
performed poorly.
</P>
<P>
Standard Life's 1.3 billion pound pension fund is ranked 65th,
having seen its investments lose 3.8pc of their value this year.
The average fund lost 0.4pc.
</P>
<P>
Phillips &AMP; Drew, the embattled value investor which parted
company with controversial chief investment officer Tony Dye only
recently, also had a difficult time.
</P>
<P>
Pension fund performance figures are highly sensitive and are
closely guarded secrets. The top of the table is dominated by
niche players which manage much smaller amounts of money.
</P>
<P>
Large pension managers are facing increasing criticism for the
secrecy with which they operate and have lost billions of pounds
worth of mandates, largely through missing out on the boom in
technology and Internet stocks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
