<HEADLINE> Earth Day Founder Shares 2000 Global Environment Leadership Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The prizes were announced by Mohamed T. El-Ashry, chief
executive officer and chairman of the Global Environment Facility
(GEF), Saturday, the 30th Earth Day.
</P>
<P>
The other winner is Anil Agarwal, director of the Center for
Science and Environment in India.
</P>
<P>
The annual award recognizes an individual, group, or
organization in government, the private sector, or the non-
government arena, for leadership of significant national or
international actions over a sustained period to protect the
global environment.
</P>
<P>
"For the last three decades, the contributions made by both
Anil Agarwal and Denis Hayes to environmental education and
awareness at the international, national and local levels have
been truly outstanding," said Dr. El-Ashry in paying tribute to
the two awardees.
</P>
<P>
The selection of Anil Agarwal and Denis Hayes for the Year 2000
award was made by Dr. El-Ashry on the advice of a panel of seven
prominent international environmentalists after an open
nominations process.
</P>
<P>
In 1970, Denis Hayes launched the Earth Day movement,
attracting 20 million people. One effect of this first great
mobilization was successful establishment of the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency, and passage of the Clean Air and
Clean Water Acts.
</P>
<P>
Today, on Earth Day 2000, the Earth Day network has mobilized
500 million people in 182 countries.
</P>
<P>
Denis Hayes was recently named by the Time magazine as one of
its 100 "Heroes of the Planet."
</P>
<P>
The award was first presented by the GEF in 1998 to President
Jose Maria Figueres of Costa Rica, and jointly in 1999 to
Professor Bert Bolin and Ambassador Bo Kjellen of Sweden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
