<HEADLINE> Cubans Happy About Elian's Exit From Miami </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Cubans woke Saturday in happiness
for the good news that the United States federal police had pulled
out six-year-old Elian Gonzalez from the home of his far-removed
relatives in Miami and took him to Washington.
</P>
<P>
Radio Reloj read early Saturday the first Cuban government
report about a U.S. government federal operation that entered at
5:05 the residence of Elian's grand-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez and
pried from his hands the minor.
</P>
<P>
The population heard via radio the second official note past 7:
15 in the morning, which said that the plane that flies with Elian
is headed to Washington and that the child is all right
</P>
<P>
The Cuban government asked the population to maintain a serene
attitude and to abstain from public demonstrations, because any
other behavior could influence negatively the future evolution of
the situation.
</P>
<P>
Juan Gonzalez, Elian's grandfather on his father side, told the
press in Cardenas, the city where the boy was born, that he felt a
great relief and happiness and that all the family was moved for a
call from Washington telling them of the exit of the child.
</P>
<P>
The news awoke all Cubans. They called each other over the
phone or knocked on the neighbors' doors to know more details
about the operation carried out by the U.S. federal police.
</P>
<P>
Five months have gone by since the retention of boy Elian
Gonzalez started and 15 days since his father, Juan Miguel, is in
Washington, waiting for his son.
</P>
<P>
Just 48 hours ago Juan Miguel had called on the U.S. people to
have his son returned, for whom he traveled to the United States,
and for the U.S. government to act and enforce the law and return
Elian.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban boy survived a wreckage in November off the U.S.
coast in which his mother and nine more people drowned. Since then
and despite his father's legal efforts to recover him, his Miami
relatives had refused to hand him over. 
</P>
