<HEADLINE> U.K. Pressures Zimbabwe with Fund Pledges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The British government Saturday
reiterated its pledge to fund a "genuine land reform program" in
Zimbabwe, but said it had to be within the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the British High Commission said British
Foreign Minister of State for African Affairs Peter Hain had made
the pledge in London, in response to deliberations at the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) leaders meeting
held in Victoria Falls of Zimbabwe on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"(South African President) Thabo Mbeki and (Mozambican
President) Joachim Chissano are right to focus on a genuine land
reform program. This is what we have always been prepared to
help fund provided it is within the rule of law," Hain said.
</P>
<P>
"This is what we will discuss with the Zimbabwean delegation in
London next Thursday; a sale and reform program and fair
elections, within the rule of law," Hain said.
</P>
<P>
He said this had been on the table since 1998 and the British
government had been waiting since that time for Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe to pick it up.
</P>
<P>
He said the violence should never have got in the way of
progress of the 1998 program.
</P>
<P>
Presidents Mbeki and Chissano Friday night said the only way
the land issue in Zimbabwe could be solved was for the donor
community to fulfil its promise it made in 1998 that it would
fund the land resettlement program.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after meeting Mugabe, on the
land situation in the country, Mbeki and Chissano said the
donors, who included Britain and the European Union, made a
commitment during the 1998 Donors Conference in Harare that they
would fund the Land Resettlement Program.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders, who were approached by Britain to restore
communication between Harare and London following differences over
 land, said they did not believe that Mugabe was using unlawful
means in his quest to solve the land issue.
</P>
<P>
"But there should be no continuation of violence on the land
issue because the country has to maintain its stability," said
Mbeki. 
</P>
