economic implications for South Africa. It is a test to see
whether Africa can accommodate the rules of the global economy,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"What has taken place in Zimbabwe is an undermining factor in
terms of foreign investment. There is no justification for the
disregard of property rights," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If there are requirements for poverty reduction, it must be
done in the proper means, not through an anarchic manner," he
added.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, SACOB met separately with the High Commissioners
of Zimbabwe and Nigeria and the acting High Commissioner for the
British Embassy in Pretoria "to gain insights from the respective
embassies into the Zimbabwean crisis", Wakeford said.
</P>
<P>
The discussions centered around the rule of law, property
rights and the sustenance of democracy relating to Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe' s handling of the occupation of hundreds
of white-owned farms by Zimbabwean veterans, according to
Wakeford.
</P>
<P>
Britain's role in Zimbabwe's land reform program and Nigeria's
 involvement in the mediation process were among other topics
discussed, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We feel hopeful there is a potential resolution in the
short-term. The land issue is now inextricably linked to the
resolution of the crisis, or at least a part of the resolution,"
Wakeford said. 
