<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Thai Govt Cautious to Japan's Swap Pact Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is reacting cautiously
to Japan's proposal to strike a regional currency swap pact with
its Asian partners to guard against future currency crises, local
analysts said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panichpakdi was recently
quoted by local media as saying that the details of the pact
should be carefully scrutinized, such as where to find the money
to engage in the currency swap pact and whether such a pact would
be beneficial to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"No pact can defend the currency unless the government's
economic policy is sound," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a Thai Finance Ministry official also said that the
Japanese proposal indicated Tokyo's hope that a regional swap
network would develop into an Asian monetary fund, a regional
version of the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
According to the local analysts, Thai government is more in
favor of setting up an Asian fund to aid countries in the region
in times of crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government had told Japanese media that it would
make the proposal at the incoming meeting of the Asian Development
Bank next month in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
It said the swap accord would include Japan, Thailand and other
Asian countries. 
