<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canberries Effective Against Cancer Risk in Mice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Cranberries could bring breast
cancer risk down by at least 40 percent in mice, opening prospects
for curing the disease on humans, Canada's National Post reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In their latest study, Canadian researchers at the University
of Western Ontario fed a group of mice with dehydrated cranberries
and then injected human breast cancer cells into the mammary
glands of mice.
</P>
<P>
Compared with another group of mice receiving injections but
without eating cranberries, this group of mice prove to be 50
percent lower in risk of suffering from breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
Drinking cranberry juice was discovered capable, too, of
reducing the number of expected tumors in the mice by 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
The cranberry-fed mice also showed a reduction in the spread of
tumors to their lungs and lymph nodes.
</P>
<P>
Najla Guthrie, the study's lead researcher, was quoted as
saying that "quercetin is the flavonoid found in cranberry juice,
and it's been shown to have activity in colon cencer in a lot of
laboratory studies."
</P>
<P>
In their next step, Canadian researchers will determine why
cranberries inhibit the development of breast cancer in animals
before they can be sure that cranberries have the same effects on
humans.
</P>
<P>
Canada is one of the major cranberry producers in the world.
More than 32,000 tons of berries were grown in 1998 to bring in 55
million Canadian dollars (about 37.3 million U.S. dollars),
according to the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amicable Solution To Zimbabwe's Land Problem Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's business magazine
Megabuck has called for an amicable solution to the land problem
to avert the deepening of an economic crisis which is threatening
the country.
</P>
<P>
In its latest publication released here Saturday, Megabuck said
if the farm invasions by ex-combatants persisted it would be
difficult for any initiatives to rescue Zimbabwe's ailing
economy, faced with the burden of foreign debt, fuel and foreign
currency shortages.
</P>
<P>
"As the tobacco selling season is approaching there is need to
ensure that no further hitches will derail it. The country relies
on foreign currency earned by tobacco and other agricultural
export products like beef and horticulture," the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
It said if foreign currency inflows from tobacco were not
forthcoming then Zimbabwe should brace for more severe shortages
that would cause industries to close.
</P>
<P>
"These sporadic invasions surely have a great opportunity cost
which must not be gambled with," it said.
</P>
<P>
The magazine noted that farmers were set to lose if they
delayed in harvesting their crops because of the farm occupations.
</P>
<P>
The ex-combatants have occupied about 1,000 white commercial
farms since February, this year.
</P>
<P>
This would force the country to import foodstuffs straining the
already stretched foreign currency stocks, it said.
</P>
<P>
"The collapse of the agricultural sector due to lawlessness
might heavily affect industrial production due to a shortage of
raw materials, leading to a decline in economic growth," it said.
</P>
<P>
It also warned that the breakdown of law displayed by the
invasions would send wrong signals to investors and the
international community that there was no peace in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
This would scare foreign investors who might believe that the
Zimbabwean economy was not conducive to business ventures.
</P>
<P>
"Investors might also be afraid of uncertainties lying in the
future since their businesses may be targets for future invasions
by the war veterans," it said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's economy is agro-based with most industrial inputs
coming from the farming and mining sectors.
</P>
<P>
Sweden has with immediate effect frozen aid to Zimbabwe over
the farm invasions while the British Airways has moved its crew
base from Zimbabwe to Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia May Extend Territorial Row Talks With Japan Beyond 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian president-elect Vladimir
Putin will likely postpone the resolution of a Russo-Japanese
territorial dispute beyond the end of this year, Kyodo News Agency
quoted a senior Russian government official as indicating on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The two countries had previously agreed to sign a peace treaty
by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
"A territorial problem is so delicate that we need a weighing-
in and preparations. And time is needed as well," Russian Vice
Foreign Minister Alexander Losyukov in charge of Asia-Pacific
issues was quoted as saying in an interview with Kyodo.
</P>
<P>
Any negotiations will require compromise, said Losyukov.
</P>
<P>
The Russian official made the remarks ahead of the first
meeting between Putin and Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori,
scheduled for April 29 in St. Petersburg, Russia.
</P>
<P>
The informal summit will provide Mori and Putin, who will be
sworn on May 7, with an occasion to become "good acquaintances,"
Losyukov said.
</P>
<P>
He declined to mention a specific date for a proposed official
visit to Japan by Putin, saying it would be decided by the two
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Russia hopes that a document covering comprehensive bilateral
relations will be issued when Putin visits Japan, he said.
</P>
<P>
In another development, former Japanese prime minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto met with former Russian president Boris Yeltsin in the
suburbs of Moscow on Saturday to discuss the territorial disputes
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, who is now chief foreign policy adviser to Japanese
Prime Minister Mori, exchanged views on the fulfillment of
agreements they reached in Russia's Krasnoyarsk in 1997 and in
Kawana, Japan, in 1998, Kyodo quoted sources close to Yeltsin as
saying.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting in Krasnoyarsk in 1997, then Russian President
Yeltsin and then Japanese Prime Minister Hashimoto agreed that
their countries would work to resolve the disputes and sign a
peace treaty by the end of 2000. But negotiations have stalled.
</P>
<P>
The territorial row involves the Russian-held islands of
Etorofu, Kunashiri and Shikotan, and the Habomai group of islets,
all off the northeastern coast of Hokkaido. They were seized by
Soviet troops at the end of World War II. 
</P>
</TEXT>
