<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Announces Aid Package to Pacific Island States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro
Mori announced an aid package for South Pacific nations Saturday
at a one-day summit with government leaders from the region in
Japan's southwestern city Miyazaki.
</P>
<P>
Under the 21-item package, Japan will contribute 4 million U.S.
dollars to promote information technology in the Pacific island
nations, fund projects in cooperation with the Untied Nations
agencies to combat infectious diseases, including AIDS, and tackle
refugee, narcotic and other problems there.
</P>
<P>
Japanese news agency Kyodo reported that in addition to
financial assistance, Japan will also provide job training for at
least 3,000 people from these countries in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
In a joint declaration issued at the end of the Pacific Islands
Leaders' Meeting (PALM) between Japan and the 16-member South
Pacific Forum (SPF), the countries pledged to step up cooperation
in sustaining economic development, tackling regional and global
problems and to strengthen partnership.
</P>
<P>
"The leaders spelled out their common vision on tomorrow's
Pacific, and their shared mid- to long-term priorities in order to
move together toward their common vision," said the "Miyazaki PALM
Declaration."
</P>
<P>
The first Japan-SPF summit was held in Tokyo in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The summit also adopted a special joint statement on
environment, with leaders agreeing to work towards implementing
the 1997 Kyoto protocol on climate change "at the earliest
possible date."
</P>
<P>
They, however, failed to agree on a specific target date,
dropping from a draft statement a phrase that said they took note
of "views expressed by many states for the protocol to come into
force by 2002."
</P>
<P>
The SPF members are deeply concerned that rising sea levels due
to global warming will lead to land erosion in low-lying islands.
</P>
<P>
The SPF was established in 1971 as a gathering of government
leaders of 14 independent and two self-governing states. They are
Australia, the Cook Islands, Fiji, Kiribati, Marshall Islands,
Micronesia, Nauru, New Zealand, Niue, Palau, Papua New Guinea,
Samoa, Tonga, Tuvalu and Vanuatu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
