<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Opposes Increase of Permanent Seats on Security Council: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Abdul Sattar said Saturday that his country will not support the
expansion of permanent members of the United Nations Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference, Sattar pledged to block the
entry into the Security Council of those nations which have not
behaved in compliance with U.N. principles, pointing a finger at
Pakistan's archrival India, which Pakistan blames for refusing to
implement U.N. resolutions on the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan's position is that we only support the proposal to
increase the number of non-permanent seats (on the UN Security
Council)," he said, adding that most of the developing countries
which Pakistan have been interacting with also hold the similar
stands.
</P>
<P>
Sattar said the United States and France have told Pakistan
they have not yet made a decision on India as a candidate for
permanent membership of the U.N. Security Council but, said they
would consider it.
</P>
<P>
"What we have been told by at least two of these countries is
that they have not yet made a decision, but what they did say is
they would consider India's proposal or candidature for a
permanent seat on the Security Council," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
