<HEADLINE> Study Still Suspended In Gaza Universities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Azhar University and the Islamic
University in Gaza are still closed on Saturday when is supposed to
be the end of classes suspension declared by the Palestinian police
last Tuesday following the bloody clashes between two factions of
students.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian police has not lifted its besiege imposed on the
campuses of the two universities, even though the number of
policemen was reduced compared with the the first days after the
eruption of the clashes which caused the injury of 35 students and
policemen.
</P>
<P>
A statement on the gate of the Islamic university said the board
of trustees decided to resume classes by next Monday, without
giving any reason for extending the suspension period, which the
police had said will be three days only starting from last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Wael Bakr, from the public relations department at the Islamic
University, told Xinhua that the initiative to solve the dispute
between the two factions of students lasted for three days only,
but it failed to reach a positive outcome.
</P>
<P>
He rejected to explain the details of the differences that led
to continuing the suspension of classes.
</P>
<P>
Sources added that the board of trustees at the two universities
intervened to solve the dispute in a bid to resume the study.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, dozens of builders reconstructed a part of a fence
surrounding the Islamic University after it was demolished by
supporters of Fatah during the clashes last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The violent clashes broke out when the pro-Hamas students at the
university tried to prevent Fatah supporters from hanging posters
carrying Arafat's photos, and due to a statement issued by the
Fatah supporters defending their victory in the student elections
held last month.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Hamas faction said the pro-Fatah group has illegally won
the recent election in the college of education of the university.
</P>
<P>
During the election of the whole Islamic University, dominated
by the Islamites, the pro-Hamas students got 71 percent of votes,
against 22 percent for the pro-Fatah supporters.
</P>
<P>
Clashes expanded at the Islamic university after students from
the neighboring Azhar University flooded to the campus to support
their colleagues, which caused the injury of 35 students, including
6 female students and 6 policemen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
