<HEADLINE> Philippine Army Launches Operations to Rescue Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Philippine government troops
Saturday launched a full scale offensive operations against the
Abu Sayyaf rebels, who are holding a group of hostages in Basilan,
the Southern Philippines, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Press Secretary Ricardo Puno said here that the army started
the operations early in the morning to rescue the hostages taken
by the rebels in their mountain hideout in Sumisip, Basilan.
</P>
<P>
By 19:00 (11:00 GMT), the operations were still going on, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government army also confirmed that they
launched the attack after the rebels claimed to have beheaded two
of the 29 hostages held by them since March 20.
</P>
<P>
"The Basilan Crisis Management Committee (CMC) had met and
decided as of Friday to request the Southern Command to mount
rescue operations to save the remaining hostages from the hands of
the Abu Sayyaf after the CMC exhausted all peaceful means and the
Abu Sayyaf showed unreasonableness," the army said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Armed Forces Chief of Staff Gen. Angelo T. Reyes denied the
claim by the Abu Sayyaf spokesman that nine soldiers were killed
and a helicopter was shot down in the attack.
</P>
<P>
Only three government soldiers were wounded in the fighting,
and all planes and helicopters returned to the base safely, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Reyes said that while the military will not guarantee that the
rescue operation will be 100 percent to save the hostages, it will
exert all efforts to ensure that the rescue operation will be a
success.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Air Force helicopter gunships fired air-to-ground
rockets and planes dropped bombs and rockets at the Abu Sayyaf
camp, reports from Basilan said.
</P>
<P>
But in response, the reports said, the Abu Sayyaf group has
threatened to behead all the hostages "if the government does not
stop the offensive."
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the rebels claimed to have beheaded two male
hostages after President Joseph Estrada ignored the Abu Sayyaf
demands for the release of three terrorists, including Ramzi
Yousef, who masterminded the World Trade Center bombing in New
York in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf also demanded the release of two local rebel
leaders jailed in Basilan on charges of bombing the police
headquarters in the province earlier this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
