<HEADLINE> Nigerian Military Forces Vow to Defend Democracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian military forces are
resolved to uphold the country's fledgling democracy, Chief of
Defence Staff Rear Admiral Ibrahim Ogohi has said.
</P>
<P>
Ogohi was quoted as saying in a statement in the capital Abuja
Friday that the declaration was necessary given recent
developments in the country and rumors that the armed forces were
interested in seizing power.
</P>
<P>
The armed forces were determined to restore their battered
image and prove their patriotism not only to their compatriots but
also the world at large, said the military chief, adding they
would defend democracy at all costs from the barracks. "We will
never abandoned our constitutional responsibility to the people of
our dear country Nigeria," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that it should also be noted that the military
forces were very determined in their effort to restore the
shattered military image in Nigeria, especially to prove to fellow
Nigerians that their patriotism was unquestionable and to show the
rest of the world that "we can protect our democracy as in more
developed countries".
</P>
<P>
The recent widespread rumors that the Nigerian armed forces
would probably overthrow the civilian government compelled the
military forces to clear the air again on its unreserved loyalty
to this elected administration, said the statement. 
</P>
