<HEADLINE> White Community Provocative Towards Black Governments: Nujoma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Namibian President Sam Nujoma has
described a majority of the white community leaving in southern
Africa as very provocative towards the black governments.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma made the remarks at the end of a meeting on the
situation prevailing in Zimbabwe regarding the land issue Friday
night in the resort town of Victoria Falls of Zimbabwe, the
Zimbabwe News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was also attended by Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe, South African President Thabo Mbeki and Mozambican
President Joachim Chissano.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian president said it was surprising that the same
people who had oppressed blacks in the continent for a long time
were now saying black governments were not observing the rule of
law.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mbeki told reporters that the land imbalance in his
country was worse than in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
He said 80 percent of the productive land was in the hands of
whites while blacks had access to only 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
"However, responses to correct the issue are different from
Zimbabwe in the sense that the development of the rest of the
economy has resulted in our people being interested in other
sectors," Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki also denied speculation from certain quarters that his
country would generate funds to resolve the land issue in
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
He said the British government and other donors who pledged to
fund the program in 1998 should do that. 
</P>
