<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Journalist Jailed for Attending Berlin Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran's prominent reformist
journalist Akbar Ganji was jailed on Saturday for attending a
controversial conference in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
Ganji, a member the editorial board of reformist daily Fatah
(conquer) was sent to prison following several hours of
interrogation and being informed of 10 complaints lodged against
him, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Intelligence Ministry, the Islamic Revolutionary Guards
Corps, the hard-line Kayhan daily, the security forces (police),
the Headquarters for Enjoining the Good and Prohibiting the Evil
and families of 13 martyrs lodged complaint against him in
connection with the Berlin conference.
</P>
<P>
Ganji became famous among journalists after he wrote a series of
stories about and urged authorities to find out the real
masterminds behind the serial political killings of opposition
leaders and dissident writers late 1998.
</P>
<P>
Ganji was detained after over 140 members of the Iranian
outgoing conservative Majlis (parliament) on Wednesday called on
the judiciary to bring to justice the Iranian reformists who
attended the conference in Berlin last week.
</P>
<P>
Hard-liners have arranged various rallies and demonstrations
throughout the country in recent days denouncing the Berlin
conference, by the Heinrich Boell Foundation on Iran after the
February parliamentary elections, in which reformists won an
overwhelming victory over the powerful conservatives.
</P>
<P>
The reformists were accused of advocating the U.S.-style reforms
in Iran at the conference, which was disrupted by members of
outlawed Mujaheddin Khalq Organization (MKO) who accused the
Iranian government of "crimes and human rights violations" in Iran
since the 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
The conference organizer had invited some close allies and
supporters of President Mohammad Khatami, including reformist
cleric Yussefi Eshkevari and reformist journalist Akbar Ganji.
</P>
<P>
Iranian conservatives, who dominate most of the sensitive organs
but suffered a series of setbacks in elections during the past two
years, said that the Berlin conference was religiously prohibited
and the judiciary has assigned the revolutionary court to probe the
case against Iranian participants.
</P>
<P>
Iranian reformists defended the Berlin conference and accused
the conservatives of trying to use the conference as a pretext to
stop the new reformist-dominated parliament from meeting and
undermining Khatami's reform programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
