<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Tunisian state-owned fertilizer producer Chenmical
plans to team up with the Union of Turkish Agricultural Credit
Cooperatives to bid for buying a fertilizer plant in Samsun,
Turkey's Black Sea province, reported Turkish Daily News on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Tunisian company, which presently supplies substantial
quantities of raw materials for diammonium phosphate production in
Turkey, will provide the raw materials for production at the Samsun
plant and capital for its upgrade in the future, said the union's
General Director, Rasit Dogan Enhos.
</P>
<P>
The partners will hold an equal stake in the company, he said.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Turkish Ministry of Labor and Social security has
drafted a bill to regulate foreign labor, reported Turkish Daily
News on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The draft envisages heavy fines on those who employ foreign
labor without permission and also on illegal foreign workers, while

permitting the employment of qualified and needed foreign staff.
</P>
<P>
Once the bill goes into effect, foreign workers will have to
apply to the Ministry of Labor and Social Security, which will
become the sole authority issuing work permits.
</P>
<P>
Approximately one million illegal foreign workers are estimated
to be employed in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's Yasar Holding's paper-making subsidiary
Viking Kagit ve Seluloz A.S. is in talks over a possible alliance
with leading hygiene goods manufacturer Swedish SCA, reported
Turkish Daily News on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The alliance is aimed at technological know-how transfer to
Turkey's fast-growing hygiene and cleaning paper products sector
and will allow Viking to expand its operations and increase exports
to neighboring markets.
</P>
<P>
Viking is Turkey's third largest cleaning paper producer and
Swedish SCA's annual production of hygiene products totals one
million tons.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- A report issued by the Customs Department showed that
Lebanon's trade deficit rose in March to 470 million U.S. dollars
from 400 million dollars in February.
</P>
<P>
The economic Egyptian daily "Alalam Elyom" on Saturday quoted
the report as saying the level of deficit in March was less than
the 530 million dollars registered in the same month of the
previous
year.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon ended the year 1999 with a trade deficit estimated at
5.53 billion dollars, against 6.3 billion dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt decided to hold an exhibition for Egyptian
products in Baghdad from April 30 to May 7, with the participation
of about 100 Egyptian companies which will display
their products in the sectors of engineering, chemical industry,
agriculture, textiles, foodstuff, pharmaceutical industry, as
well as sectors of contracting and construction.
</P>
<P>
The economic Egyptian daily "Alalam Elyom" said on Saturday
quoted the chairman of the Egyptian General Authority for
Exhibitions and
International Markets, Mohamed El Saleh, as saying that the
Authority received many requests for participating in this event.
</P>
<P>
Saleh affirmed that the Authority attaches a special importance
to the exhibition since the Iraqi market is one of the promising
markets for the Egyptian products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
