<HEADLINE> 2nd Lead: S.Lankan Rebels Overrun Major Military Complex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's rebels of Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) claimed Saturday they had overrun a
strategic military complex in northern Jaffna peninsula after two
days of heavy fighting.
</P>
<P>
"Iyakachchi and Elephant Pass bases forming the giant military
complex of the Sri Lankan army on the gateway to Jaffna fell to
the combat formations of the Liberation Tigers this afternoon,"
said the rebels in a statement from their London office.
</P>
<P>
There were no immediate comment from the Ministry of Defense.
</P>
<P>
The rebel statement said more than 1,000 government soldiers
were killed on Saturday but did not give their own casualties.
</P>
<P>
"The conquest of Elephant Pass complex, the largest and well-
entrenched military base in the north, signified a major military
victory of the Tigers in the current campaign against Sri Lankan
troops in Jaffna," the LTTE said.
</P>
<P>
It said the fall of this crucial base at the gate of Jaffna
will facilitate the LTTE to gain its strategic goal of retaking
their former stronghold of Jaffna which they lost in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels, fighting for a separate homeland for minority
Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east since 1983, have intensified
their offensives since late March around Iyakachchi and the
Elephant Pass.
</P>
<P>
The renewed clashes in northern Sri Lanka came amid moves by
Norway to bring the LTTE and the government here to the
negotiating table. Both sides have agreed to Norwegian involvement,
but dates for direct talks have not been agreed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
