<HEADLINE> Nigerian Senator's Plot to Impeach Obasanjo Condemned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Nobel literature laureate
Wole Soyinka has added his voice to a national condemnation of an
attempt by maverick senator Arthur Nzeribe to impeach President
Olusegun Obasanjo after his only one year in office.
</P>
<P>
Soyinka said here on Friday that Nzeribe was only seeking
attention, the News Agency of Nigeria reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"There is nothing else he is looking for except attention, so
don't give it to him. Ignore him," said the renowned playwright.
</P>
<P>
Nzeribe Monday circulated a 15-point petition accusing Obasanjo
of nepotism, disregard for the constitution and the awarding of
oil contracts to his "cronies and kinsmen."
</P>
<P>
Nzeribe followed up with a senate appearance that caused a stir
on Tuesday, when fellow angry senators almost tore him apart. But
he insisted the president had a case to answer and that he had the
right under the constitution to press for it.
</P>
<P>
In a rare show of solidarity, politicians of the opposition
Alliance for Democracy Thursday marched to the office of the
Lagos State Governor Ahmed Bola Tinubu, urging him to initiate a
law declaring Nzeribe persona-non- grata in the state.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo himself has shrugged off the impeachment threat,
telling journalists: "I am fine."
</P>
<P>
The senate has meanwhile referred Nzeribe's petition to its
committee on privileges and public petition for possible
discussion after the Easter holidays. 
