<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP on Relationship Between Poverty, Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's poverty reduction is a
pre- condition for the success of health reforms against poverty,
the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In its Human Development Report for Zimbabwe for 1999 released
here, the UNDP said poverty, which had worsened since the late
1980s, was one of the strongest factors in the prevalence of
various infectious and non- infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
"Poverty has a direct bearing on the health status of people
and causes an increase in sick people. Health is thus a factor in
sound economic development. At the same time, a prosperous
society promotes the health status of the population," it said.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP said the two-way relationship between health and
economic developments suggested that poverty reduction was a
pre-condition for the success of health reforms against poverty.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has been experiencing high levels of poverty in the
urban and rural areas and the situation has been worsened by the
increasing economic crisis which has seen companies closing down
and large-scale retrenchments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
