<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Boy Finally to Reunite With Father Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Services (INS) removed by force the six-year-old
Cuban shipwreck survivor from his relatives' home in Little Havana,
Miami, early on Saturday, and the father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, is
expected to reunite with his son at the Andrews Air Force Base
soon.
</P>
<P>
Gonzalez, who arrived in Washington for taking custody of his
son on April 4, has gone to the airport for the reunion.
</P>
<P>
A group of INS agents arrived at the house of the Miami
relatives shortly after 5 a.m. (0900 GMT) to knock and kick on the
door. A short time later, Elian Gonzalez was brought out of the
home by a woman agent, put into a van and whisked away. The boy
was then put on a airplane heading to Washington.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno told a press conference that
Elian is safe. She stressed that the government tried every way it
could to get the family of the Miami relatives to surrender the
boy, before taking the action, but the negotiations failed and the
family refused to turn over the boy.
</P>
<P>
Reno said the paramount concern for the morning's raid was the
safety of the child.
</P>
<P>
She said eight federal agents were in the house and one female
agent picked up Elian. She spoke with him in Spanish. The whole
process lasted for three minutes.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton approved the pre-dawn raid to seize
the boy, his spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was kept informed throughout the night of the progress
of the negotiations between the Justice Department and Gonzalez's
relatives, Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
After being told by his chief of staff John Podesta that all-
night negotiations to resolve the custody dispute failed, Clinton
said that he was disappointed and gave the go-ahead for seizing
Elian from the Miami home of his great uncle Lazaro Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
"The president was pleased the boy was safe and going to be
reunited with his father," Lockhart said, adding that the
president had no plans to meet with Elian's father.
</P>
<P>
The father expressed his gratitude to the U.S. authorities. "We
are grateful to the attorney general and the Department of Justice
for upholding the law with utmost concern for the safety and well-
being of Elian Gonzalez," the father's attorney, Greg Craig, said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The attorney general was tireless. She was insistent that we
continue our effort to achieve a peaceful and voluntary transfer
of custody."
</P>
<P>
"We too are sad that force was required, but to the very end
Lazaro Gonzalez placed road blocks in the path of an orderly
transfer of custody. He gave the attorney general no alternative."
</P>
<P>
Craig said the boy is in good spirits on the airplane and eager
to be reunited with his family.
</P>
<P>
Reno said that the Justice Department will abide by an appeals
court rule that the boy will remain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta
issued an order that keeps Elian in the United States pending an
appeal for an asylum filed by the relatives in Miami for the boy.
</P>
<P>
Elian was rescued on November 25 near a shipwreck in the
Atlantic sea off Florida after his mother and 10 others drowned
when their boat capsized.
</P>
<P>
Early in the year, the INS ruled that the boy belongs to his
father and should be returned to Cuba. However, the Miami
relatives insist the boy should stay with them in the United
States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Residents Told to Change Daily Habits for Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Sydney residents had been told
to change their coummuting habits during the Olympic Games to
ensure the Games run somoothly, according to reports on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
IOC vice-president Anita DeFrantz said that while the
foundation for Sydney's public transport system during the Games
was in place, it was up to the city's residents to ensure its
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
"It's going to require people to change their daily habits,"
DeFrantz was quoted as saying. "It may mean getting up a little
earlier and going to work, it may mean going to work a little bit
later or perhaps going to work at a different time or going on
vacation."
</P>
<P>
DeFrantz is in Sydney heading a three-member delegation of the
IOC's transport working group.
</P>
<P>
She suggested Sydneysiders stay off public transport at peak
times, for the benefit of athletes and spectators.
</P>
<P>
"It would help if you have some place else you could be; you
could watch it on television," she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
