<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earth Day Observed Across China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 80 billion yuan (9.64
billion U.S. dollars) is spent annually for fighting pollution in
China.
</P>
<P>
At a function today to mark Earth Day, Qu Geping, chairman of
the Environment and Resources Protection Committee of the 9th
National People's Congress, said the amount accounts for 0.6
percent of China's GDP, the highest input among all developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
There is unprecedented attention being paid to protecting the
environment, he said, adding that the central government has
listed environmental protection as one of the most important tasks
in its drive to develop the country's western regions.
</P>
<P>
The general public have enthusiastically taken part in
environmental protection campaigns. In Beijing alone, there are
more than 40 non-governmental environmental protection
organizations engaged in improving the environment and spreading
public awareness.
</P>
<P>
Today's function, held at Imperial Palace, was sponsored by six
non-governmental organizations. A campaign to encourage people to
grow more trees and a China Earth Week were also discussed at the
Meeting.
</P>
<P>
Similar Earth Day celebrating activities were held today in
Kunming, Shanghai and Wuhan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
