<HEADLINE> Final Israeli Pullout From West Bank To Be Discussed Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian sources asserted that a
meeting will be held on Sunday between chief Palestinian
negotiator, Saeb Erekat and his Israeli counterpart Oded Eran to
discuss the last phase of the Israeli pullout from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
However, the sources quoted by the daily "Alayam" on Saturday
did not disclose the venue of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Israel has proposed to implement a part of
the troops redeployment before this month, including some
Palestinian villages near Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the sources pointed out that this proposal has not
been approved yet, since it will be the focus of the meeting held
between the two sides during this week.
</P>
<P>
Under Oslo agreement, Israel should withdraw its troops from all
West Bank and Gaza except Jerusalem , the settlements, and the
military areas before the start of the final status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The final status talks went on for almost six months, including
two rounds of talks held in Washington, but the two sides did not
make any progress on the issues of Jerusalem, borders, refugees,
and the settlements owing to the wide gap between their stances.
</P>
<P>
After the talks held Thursday in Washington between Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat and the U.S. President Bill Clinton, it was
declared that the third round of the final status talks will be
held on April 30 in Eilat, and will be attended by the U.S peace
coordinator, Dennis Ross, in a bid to help reach a frame agreement
by next month.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Palestinian delegation in the negotiations, Yasser
Abed Rabbo, said next moves will be decided during this round,
while Erekat stated that another round may be required to reach a
frame accord.
</P>
<P>
During Washington summit , Clinton assured Arafat that the U.S
will play a greater role and will exert all its efforts to push
ahead the peace process to help the Israeli and the Palestinian
sides achieve a lasting peace by September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
