<HEADLINE> 3,000 Illegal Chicks Bound for Congo Destroyed in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Three thousand chicks illegally en
route to the Democratic Republic of the Congo from South Africa
have been set ablaze by the Zambian Veterinary Department after
being seized from Ndola Airport in its Copperbelt Province on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The one-day old chicks which were packed in 30 carton boxes
were spread with formalin to suffocate them before they were set
alight in Itawa township on Friday, Saturday's Zambia Daily Mail
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Francis Mulenga, principal veterinary officer in
charge of Copperbelt and North-Western provinces, as saying the
importer of the chicks, Kim Poultry of Lubumbashi in the DRC, did
not have documentation to allow it to transit through Zambia and
risked spreading the deadly new castle disease which is fatal in
chickens.
</P>
<P>
"We are not trying to be harsh on anyone, we are trying to
protect our industry and more over the law requires one to get
papers," Mulenga said.
</P>
<P>
He said the department did not know about the illegal
importation of the chicks and that what raised suspicion about Kim
Poultry was its usage of a Zambian registered vehicle to ferry the
chicks to Lubumbashi, but they could have been diverted anywhere
within Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Kim Poultry did not have a stock movement permit authorized by
the Veterinary Department, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
