<HEADLINE> Bomb Alert Evacuates Supermarket in Brittany, France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- A supermarket of the Carrefour
chain stores in Brittany, western France, had to be evacuated on
Saturday after receiving a bomb alert, days after a blast killed a
woman employee in a McDonald's restaurant in the same region.
</P>
<P>
The paramilitary gendarmerie said an anonymous phone call said
late in the morning that a bomb would blow up the supermarket in
half an hour, forcing the store to evacuate hundreds of customers
shopping for the Christian Easter this weekend.
</P>
<P>
Police cordoned off the store while fire brigades and
paramilitary police began checking the huge surface of the market
in Saint-Brieuc-Langueux.
</P>
<P>
Hours earlier, another McDonald's restaurant in France came
under attack as a fire accident broke out at dawn Saturday at a
children's playground belonging to the restaurant near Bayonne in
the Basque region in southwest France.
</P>
<P>
Police said that the arsonists apparently were inspired by
Wednesday's bombing attack, which has made McDonald's top news in
France this week.
</P>
<P>
A militant Brittany group called "Brittany Revolutionary Army (
ARB)" is the number one suspect in Wednesday's attack.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, police also suspect the ARB had provided the Spanish
Basque separatist group ETA with logistic support.
</P>
<P>
French police recently arrested a 26-year-old woman militant of
ETA in the French Basque region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Laurence Turbec, a 27-year-old woman employee of
McDonald's who was killed in the Wednesday's attack, was buried in
a private funeral on Saturday in her hometown in Lehon, Brittany.
</P>
</TEXT>
