<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Gets 392.8 Mln U.S. Dollars of PFI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has attracted a total
of 392.8 million U.S. dollars of private foreign investment (PFI)
in the first nine months of the current fiscal year, a net
increase of 18.9 million dollars over the same period of last
financial year, according to latest figures released by the State
Bank of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The PFI inflow into Pakistan during July 1998-March 1999 was
recorded at 373.9 million dollars, including 369.2 million dollars
in the foreign direct investment (FDI) and 4.7 million dollars in
the portfolio investment.
</P>
<P>
The total investment in the first nine months of 1999-2000
included 360.5 million dollars of FDI and 32.3 million dollars of
portfolio investment.
</P>
<P>
Britain has topped the list with a total private investment of
153.7 million dollars in the first nine months of the current
fiscal year, a 100-plus percent increase over the previous
corresponding period.
</P>
<P>
The major chunk of FDI has been made in the chemical,
pharmaceutical and fertilizer sector which showed a growth of
nearly 165 percent.
</P>
<P>
There has also been a tremendous growth in the FDI inflow in
the food, beverages and tobacco group. In the first nine months,
this group has drawn an investment of 49.1 million dollars,
compared with the mere 6.6 million dollars previously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
