<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Ugandan People Use Condom to Prevent AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Condoms have been widely used in
Uganda over the past five years, which have contributed much to
the sharp decline of HIV/AIDS prevalence in the east African
country, the New Vision daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The rate of men who use condoms to guard against HIV/AIDS
skyrocketed from seven percent to 40 percent, and the proportion
of women who use family planning methods also grew from 13 percent
to 21 percent during the 1995-99 period, according to an
evaluation survey by the Delivery of Improved Service for Health
project (DISH) in the country.
</P>
<P>
The DISH project has contributed to improvement in health
habits to more than seven million men, women and children in
Uganda, said Dish project country director Cheryl Letternma during
the launching of the second phase work plan for Rakai district.
</P>
<P>
She said that women in the DISH operational area, who give
birth with the aid of doctors or qualified mid-wives, shot up from
55 percent to 64 percent in the same period.
</P>
<P>
Population in the DISH project areas who have gone for HIV
blood tests, has increased from one percent to 21 percent and one
percent to 15 percent among men and women respectively, Letternma
said.
</P>
<P>
The project intends to continue supporting health services in
the operational areas, especially in the field of reproductive and
maternal health including children and family planning, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
