<HEADLINE> Ford Motor To End Production At Dagenham </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 22 (Xinhua) - Ford Motor Co, the world's second
largest auto maker, is set to announce the end of car production
at its Dagenham plant in Britain, putting 3,000 jobs at risk, it
is reported.
</P>
<P>
The move will be announced in mid-May as part of a major
restructuring that will affect other Ford European plants,
according to the Financial Times.
</P>
<P>
Intense price competition, the strength of the pound abroad and
surplus capacity have undermined the competitiveness of Ford's
operations in Britain, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In February, Ford axed 1,500 jobs at Dagenham, its largest
British plant, and warned it could take further steps to turn
around its loss-making European car business.
</P>
<P>
The termination of car production at Dagenham, that employs
more than 7,700 people, is another blow to the British motor
industry, resulting from the expected loss of thousands of jobs
when BMW sells ailing Rover.
</P>
<P>
Ford declined to comment on the future of car assembly at
Dagenham plant, but told the paper that an announcement would be
made in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
Dagenham's future has been in doubt for months. Managers have
criticized poor productivity and the plant has been hit by
unofficial strikes and allegations of work force racism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
