<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Parliament Speaker in Saudi Arabia to Enhance Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UWAIT CITY, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Speaker of Kuwait's National
Assembly Jassem Al-Khorafi arrived in the Saudi capital of Riyadh
Saturday for a three-day visit to boost cooperation between
parliaments of the two gulf nations.
</P>
<P>
Al-Khorafi will meet with the head of the Saudi Shura
(Consultative) Council and Saudi government officials in Riyadh and
the western Saudi city of Jeddah, the Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The visit, the first to Saudi Arabia by Al-Khorafi since he was
elected the Speaker in July last year, is in the "framework of
increasing cooperation, exchanging views and expertise in the
parliamentary field, and in democratic practice" in both countries,
the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait is the only Gulf Arab country that has an elected
parliament, while Saudi Arabia, along with other Gulf states of
Bahrain, Oman, Qatar and the United Arab Emirates, are maintaining
a consultative system.
</P>
<P>
In early 1992, Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz decided to
establish the Saudi Shura Council and named Sheikh Mohammed Bin
Ibrahim Bin Jubair as the chairman of the consultative body. The
council does not exercise legislative power of the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Kuwait news agency on Friday, Bin
Jubair underlined the importance of the visit of the Kuwaiti
parliament delegation to exchange opinion in the parliamentary
affairs and democratic practices.
</P>
<P>
He described the Kuwaiti parliamentary experience as "unique."
</P>
<P>
Bin Jubair also voiced support for the idea of forming a Gulf
parliament union, noting that the "existence of the current
consultative councils in the Gulf Arab states needs to be
developed." But he did not elaborate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Bombard Hits School in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli forces bombed several
villages in south Lebanon Saturday morning and the shell hit a new
school in the village of Ibgeen, People's Voice radio station
reported.
</P>
<P>
There was no immediate report on casualties after the raids.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian- and Syrian-backed Hezbollah guerrillas fired 10
Katyushas to two Israeli positions at Blaat and Tal Halfa in west
sector of south Lebanon. The Israeli radio confirmed the attacks
from guerrillas but did not release any damage result.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli occupation forces and the resistance guerrillas
intensified fightings after Israel formally notified the United
Nations that it would pullout its troops from south Lebanon by
July.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak noted last week that his
country will harshly retaliate if the guerrillas continue firing
Katyushas to north Israel or cause any casualties after the Israeli
troops' withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel has occupied parts of south Lebanon since 1978. It set up
the present "security zone" in 1985 saying it needed to protect its
northern settlements from cross-border guerrilla attacks.
Hezbollah, or Party of God, has since then been leading a war of
attrition to end the Israeli occupation of south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
