<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Economy Growing Below Potential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's economy is
currently growing below its actual potential, Finance Ministry
Adviser Mustapa Mohamed said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"We have a long-term potential of growing at 7.0 percent a year.
Our task is to work harder to realize this potential," he told a
seminar here.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's economy has recovered since the second half of last
year. In the 2000 Budget re-tabled last February, Malaysia's GDP
is projected to expand by 5.8 percent this year, an upward target
from 5.0 percent set earlier.
</P>
<P>
"The 5.8 percent growth estimated for this year is well below
our actual capacity," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has worked hard towards national
economic betterment by implementing various measures and
regulations.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia recorded a 5.4 percent GDP growth last year, against
an earlier estimation of 4.3 percent, after contracting 7.5
percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian Institute of Economic Research (MIER), the
country's leading economic think-tank, has forecast the GDP growth
at 6.0 percent this year in a report released earlier this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
