<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Suspends Permit for Foreign Workers Recruitment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has decided to
suspend the issuance of permits for the recruitment of foreign
workers, Home Ministry Secretary-General Jamaluddin Haji Ahmad
Damanhuri said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The move was taken as the ministry is studying the situation
with regard to the recruitment of foreign workers in all sectors,
Haji said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
For applications which were already approved, he added,
employers could continue to go to the Immigration Department
Headquarters to pay levy and other charges for obtaining visa
approvals needed for foreign workers to be brought into the
country.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's Cabinet Committee on Foreign Workers decided on
February 28 that the Home Ministry would stop accepting new
applications for the recruitment of foreign workers for the time
being as it was still processing a large number of applications
submitted earlier.
</P>
<P>
By February this year, there were 697,219 legal foreign workers
in Malaysia, with 517,766 of them from Indonesia, 129,000 from
Bangladesh, 30,500 from Philippines, 3,280 from Pakistan, 2,888
from Thailand and the balance from other countries, according to
official figures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
