<HEADLINE> Kenya to Equip Hospitals, Health Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government plans to
equip all highway hospitals and other health facilities for
accident emergencies, Permanent Secretary Julius Meme for Health
Ministry has said.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper Saturday quoted Meme as
saying the idea of equipping highway hospitals and health
facilities is to cope with the increasing road accidents.
</P>
<P>
Meme made the remarks in the capital Nairobi Friday when he
received the survivors of a bus-lorry head-on crash on Thursday
along the Nairobi- Mombasa Highway which killed 73 people.
</P>
<P>
The most targeted are those near known black spots along
Kericho road in Western Province and Nairobi-Mombasa Highway
including Voi's Moi Hospital, Kericho Hospital and Naivasha
Hospital, he said.
</P>
<P>
The permanent secretary noted that most hospitals had doctors
but lacking facilities to handle emergencies, saying his ministry
is sourcing for local and external donors for the project.
</P>
<P>
Due to speeding, overloading and ruthless driving, road
accidents in Kenya are seen on rise recently. On March 29, two
buses had a head-on collision in western Kenya, killing 76
passengers on board, the worst ever of its kind recorded in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
