<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of HIV-Positive Russians to Hit 1 Million in Two Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The number of Russians who are HIV-
positive will exceed 1 million within two years, the Russian Anti-
AIDS Center said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Professor Vadim Pokrovsky, head of the center, told the press
that AIDS has been spreading faster in Russia in recent years with
7,000 more HIV cases registered so far this year.
</P>
<P>
Pokrovsky predicted that the number of registered HIV cases
would exceed 300,000 by the year's end, which would be a two-fold
increase compared with last year's figures.
</P>
<P>
The number will reach 1 million in two years, he warned.
</P>
<P>
"They are mostly young people. As many as 80 percent of all HIV-
infected people are aged 15 to 25. That means an entire generation
is perishing here," Pokrovsky said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
