<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Police Removes Cuban Boy Away From Relatives by Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON,April 22 (Xinhua) -- The six-year-old Cuban
shipwreck survivor Elian Gonzalez was removed by U.S. federal
agents by force from the his relatives' home in Miami early
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The agents fired tear gas to the crowd as they left the house,
an Associated Press report quoted witnesses as saying.
</P>
<P>
The witnesses said the agents arrived at the house shortly
after 5 a.m. (0900 GMT) to knock and kick on the door. A short
time later, Elian was brought out of the home by a woman agent,
put into a van and whisked away.
</P>
<P>
A crowd of several hundred people were still gathering around
the house and emotions were high.
</P>
<P>
The boy was reportedly flown to Washington to reunite with his
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who arrived in the United States on
April 6 for the reunion with his son.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno refused to set a
timetable for reuniting Elian with his father after meeting with
the latter.
</P>
<P>
After the 15-minute meeting at the Justice Department with
Gonzalez, Reno said in a short statement that she told him that "I
could not commit to a particular course of action or timetable."
</P>
<P>
"I was deeply moved by Mr. Gonzalez' evident love for his son...
I assured him I would continue working toward the goal of
reuniting him with his child," Reno said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
Reno said the father expressed great concern for and requested
a quick reunion with the boy, who has been in the United States
for nearly five months since he survived in the Atlantic sea off
Florida. The boy's mother and 10 others were all drowned.
</P>
<P>
The meeting took place as Reno, having exhausted almost all
options, was waiting for her law enforcement officials to
determine how to have the boy transferred to his father.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton said Thursday that Elian should be
promptly and orderly reunited with his father.
</P>
<P>
Clinton told reporters at the White House that there is "no
conceivable argument" to keep Elian and his father apart after a
federal appeals court ruled the boy cannot leave the United States.
</P>
<P>
"I think he should be reunited with his son. That is the law
and the main argument of the family in Miami for not doing so has
now been removed," Clinton told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the boy's father asked Americans to write
to Clinton and Attorney General Reno to pressure them to reunite
him with Elian.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta
issued an order that keeps Elian in the United States pending an
appeal for an asylum filed by the relatives in Miami for the boy.
</P>
</TEXT>
