<HEADLINE> Tanaka Attacks World Record in National Swimming Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Masami Tanaka sent a strong message
to the coming Olympic Games as she broke her own national record
twice in the women's 200-meter breaststroke on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Tanaka, who set an earlier record of two minutes 26.18 seconds
in the morning, improved it by clocking 2:24.27 in the semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
Her time is faster than the winning mark of 2:25.45 set by
Hungarian Agnes Kovacs in the 1998 World Championships in Perth
and the Atlanta Olympic winning time of 2:25.41 set by Penny Heyns
of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The current world record of 2:23.64 was set by Heyns in the Pan
Pacific championships in Sydney in August last year.
</P>
<P>
It was Tanaka's fifth national record of the week after setting
another three on her way to winning the 100-meter breaststroke in
1:07.27 on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
