<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Ruling Party Begins Race for Zanzibar Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian ruling Chama Cha
Mapinduzi (CCM) party has started its candidates nomination for
the Zanzibar Presidency, media here reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Two prominent members of CCM, Transport and Communication
Minister Amani Abeid Karume and Ambassador Ahmed Hassan Diria,
Friday collected the nomination forms after being requested by CCM
elders.
</P>
<P>
Karume is the son of Zanzibar's founder President, the late
Abeid Karume, and Diria is chairman of the Tanzania Communications
Commission and former Foreign Affairs Minister.
</P>
<P>
Other CCM leaders expected to enter the Zanzibar Presidential
race include Vice-President Omar Ali Juma, retired President Ali
Hassan Mwinyi, Home Affairs Minister Mohamed Seif Khatib and
Zanzibar Chief Minister Dr. Mohammed Gharib Billal.
</P>
<P>
Further more, Speaker of the House of Representatives Ameir
Kificho, Minister of State in the Prime Minister's Office
(Information and Policy) Ali Ameir Mohamed, Finance Minister Amina
Salum Ali, and CCM Deputy Secretary General Mohamed Takrima are
also expected to join the race.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar, including the main Unguja island and its sister
island of Pemba lying some 40 kilometers east of the mainland of
Tanzania, merged with the then Republic of Tanganyika in 1964 to
form the United Republic of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
But Zanzibar has its own government, president and parliament
dealing with affairs except foreign and defense ones.
</P>
<P>
Though the Union President Benjamin Mkapa, who is also chairman
of the CCM, seems to have no strong candidate from the opposition,
it is hard for the CCM to find a right candidate to defeat Seif
Shariff Hamad, candidate of Zanzibar's main opposition party Civic
United Front (CUF).
</P>
<P>
In the 1995 presidential elections, the outgoing CCM President
of Zanzibar Salmin Amour defeated Seif by a 51 to 49 percentage
margin.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania will hold its second multi-party general elections on
October 29, this year to elect the Union President, Members of
Parliament and Zanzibar President, Members of the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
According to a timetable issued by the National Election
Committee, the registration of voters will be conducted between
August 1 and 21 while nomination of contestants will be made on
August 13, and election campaigns between August 14 and October
28.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first time in the country's post-independence
history for presidential, parliamentary and civic elections to be
held simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
At least 13 fully registered political parties including the
CUF which is the main opposition party in Zanzibar are expected to
start before May the primary elections, which are likely to be
dominated by the ruling CCM at least on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
President Mkapa, who won the 1995 elections, is expected to run
for his second five-year term.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania had a single political party, the CCM, from 1965 until
1992 when the multiparty system was introduced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, April 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA -- The Central Asian countries of Kazakhstan,
Uzbekistan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan signed Friday a treaty on
jointly combating terrorism, religious extremism, organized crime
and other factors threatening regional security and stability,
news reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Under the treaty, signed in Tashkent, capital of Uzbekistan, by
presidents from the four nations, they will unite as one in
maintaining security and stability in Central Asia by taking
timely and effective steps to curb terrorism and extremism
threatening the region, the Central Asian Interfax news agency
reported. (Kazakhstan-Central Asia-Anti-terrorism)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- NATO dropped tens of thousands of depleted uranium
bombs on eight locations in Yugoslavia during last year's
airstrikes, causing widespread environmental damage, a Yugoslav
government report said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report, prepared by both Yugoslav and foreign experts, was
based on a yearlong study on the environmental effects of the NATO
airstrikes. Large numbers of depleted uranium bombs banned by
international laws were dropped by NATO warplanes in southern part
of Serbia and Montenegro, which made the degree of radioactive
contamination there 1,000 times above the normal level, said
Yugoslav Assistant Defense Minister Slobodan Petkovich. (
Yugoslavia-NATO-Uranium Bombs)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KIEV -- The Ukrainian Foreign Ministry welcomed the Russian
State Duma's ratification of the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (
CTBT) Friday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a statement that the Russian parliament's
approval of the Strategic Arms Reduction Talks (START) II and the
CTBT would produce a positive influence on the process of nuclear
nonproliferation and disarmament. (Ukraine-Russia-CTBT Approval)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PANMUNJOM, South Korea -- South Korea and the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) have agreed to hold a second
preparatory meeting for the agreed inter-Korean summit on June 12-
14.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at the first preparatory meeting held
in the Peace House south of the truce village Saturday morning.
Delegations from Seoul and Pyongyang agreed to hold the second
meeting at Tongilgak, a house north of the truce village, at 10 a.
m. local time (0100 GMT) next Thursday. (SKorea-DPRK-Summit)
</P>
</TEXT>
