<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Have Stable Food Supply in 2000: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Russia will harvest 70-80 million
tons of grain in 2000, which will keep the country safe from
serious food shortage, Russian Deputy Prime Minister Vladimir
Shcherbak told a news conference Friday.
</P>
<P>
As much as 7.5-8 percent of that amount will be lost in
processing and storing, but food supply will be stable in 2000, he
said.
</P>
<P>
However, it would not be true to say that Russian agriculture
has come out of its crisis, and it would take years to recover
completely, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the spring sowing in Chechnya, Shcherbak said an area of 80,
000 hectares will be sown there although it would be cheaper to
transfer foodstuffs to the republic from outside because the
agricultural infrastructure and machinery in the province are in
ruins.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, First Deputy Agriculture and Food Minister Anatoly
Mikhalyov said that Russia will not need the so-called big package
of U.S. food aid if 70-75 million tons of grain is harvested this
year as planned.
</P>
<P>
"The shipment to Russia of the last lot of U.S. maize, part of
the 1999 food aid program at an amount of 474,000 tons, is nearing
completion. At the end of May and in early June, 300,000 tons of
wheat from the so-called small package of U.S. food aid in 2000
will arrive and ease the situation on the Russian grain market
before a new harvest," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
