<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Improve Registration Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The work to directly elect
township people's deputies from November to February proved to be
no easy job, so Beijing vows to make it easier in the future.
</P>
<P>
Traditional way to register voters should be reformed and
greater efforts should be made to attract people to vote, said
Zhang Xuming, Director of the Sub-Committee of Internal Affairs of
the Standing Committee of the 11th Beijing Municipal People's
Congress (BMPC), said Friday on the last day of the standing
committee's two-day session.
</P>
<P>
Like the rest of the country, Beijing registers its voters and
then defines constituencies on people's residence cards. However
with the development of the market economy, more and more
population shifts are taking place, and the registration of voters
has become one major headache for relevant officials.
</P>
<P>
Zhang predicted that the difficulty will become even greater,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Although Zhang failed to suggest specific reform measures for
the already out-of-date way of registering voters, this is the
first time a leading BMPC official in charge of voter registration
suggested reform measures during a session of the BMPC Standing
Committee.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang, Voters' ignorance about the candidates'
background and what the candidates will do once they become people
's deputies have seriously dampened their enthusiasm about voting.
</P>
<P>
Although things did change for the better when the BMPC
Standing Committee began to promote city meetings between
candidates and voters in 1998, the meetings still needed to be
systematized and spread out further to be more effective.
</P>
<P>
"We should also step up publicity on the functions of the
system of People's Congress, and of the deputies," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has staged three direct elections since 1996, one for
people's deputies at the level of county and district and two for
those at the level of town and township. Participation rate was
over 95 percent. The rate for the one closed in February was 97.05
percent.
</P>
<P>
About 2.7 million voters from 224 suburban towns and townships
around Beijing produced altogether 11,677 new deputies for the
people's congresses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
