<HEADLINE> Weekly Highlights of Diplomatic News (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of major diplomatic
news in the week from April 15 through 21:
</P>
<P>
 Parliamentary Diplomacy
</P>
<P>
-- Li Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee of the Chinese
National People's Congress (NPC), met last Wednesday with a
delegation of the Party of Social Democracy of Romania, headed by
Adrian Nastase, first vice-president of the Party of Social
Democracy of Romania and also vice-president of the Chamber of
Deputies of Romania.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao met last Wednesday with
Lawrence Gonzi, visiting deputy leader of the Malta Nationalist
Party, who also serves as deputy prime minister and minister of
social policy and relations with parliament.
</P>
<P>
-- NPC Standing Committee Vice-Chairwoman He Luli told Freitas
Neto, senator of the Brazilian Congress and head of a delegation
of the Liberal Front Party of Brazil, last Monday that China's NPC
wishes to expand exchanges with the Brazilian Congress at all
levels. She also met with a Vietnamese delegation led by Tran Van
Tuan, chairman of the Hanoi People's Council and a member of the
Central Committee of the Communist Party of Viet Nam last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
-- Four aides to members of the U.S. House of Representatives
International Relations Committee arrived in Lhasa, capital of the
Tibetan Autonomous Region, last Monday for a four-day visit. The
guests will visit some lamaseries, schools and households during
their stay there.
</P>
<P>
Military Foreign Relations
</P>
<P>
-- Zhang Wannian, vice-chairman of China's Central Military
Commission, last Friday told visiting Chief Commander of the
Australian Defense Forces Christopher Barrie that China will by no
means allow any form of "Taiwan independence" or foreign
interference in the Taiwan issue, nor will it let the Taiwan issue
remain unsettled without time limit.
</P>
<P>
In a separate meeting with Jaromir Novotny, the first deputy
defense minister of the Czech Republic, Zhang said that the
reunification of the motherland is favored by the majority of the
people and is the general trend. Any attempt to create "
independence" for Taiwan is doomed to failure, he said.
</P>
<P>
-- A delegation of the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA)
left here last Friday for an official goodwill visit to Argentina,
Chile and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
-- Kui Fulin, deputy chief of PLA's General Staff, held talks
Friday with Houssein Abdel Khalek, secretary-general of the
Lebanese Supreme Defense Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
