<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Rescuers Retrieve 128 Bodies of Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Philippine rescuers have retrieved
128 bodies of the 131 passengers and crew of the ill-fated Air
Philippines flight 541 that crashed on Samal Island early
Wednesday morning, an official report said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Philippine News Agency said that 128 bodies have
been found, and at least 55 of them been identified as of Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
With only three more bodies to be recovered, the agency said,
the composite task force is now busy conducting mopping-up
operations at the crash site, about seven miles (11 km) from the
Davao International Airport.
</P>
<P>
The pace of identifying the charred remains of the victims was
expected to quicken with the deployment of a team of international
forensic experts at the crash site on Samal Island near the
southern city of Davao, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Filipino forensic investigators from the National
Bureau of Investigation, led by Dr. Max Reyes arrived in Davao. On
Friday, five experts from Britain flew in to assist their local
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
The focus of activity now shifted to the forensic
investigations of the remains, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the forensic team started collecting blood samples
from the victims' relatives for DNA matching with the blood and
body tissue recovered from the site.
</P>
<P>
The bodies have been transferred to two local funeral parlors
where they will undergo a more technical identification process.
</P>
<P>
Air Philippines said that it is shouldering all costs of burial
or cremation.
</P>
<P>
A Catholic mass and an Islamic prayer service were scheduled
for Saturday at both the crash site and the Mercure Grand Hotel in
Davao City, where relatives of the crash victims are billeted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
