<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Army Shells Rebel Camp: Radio Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government army
Saturday shelled a camp of Muslim rebels, who abducted 29 hostages
a month ago and claimed to have killed two of them, a local radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
Radio Station DXRC said that government army shelled a camp of
Abu Sayyaf in the southern province of Basilan with cannons and
mortars early Saturday. But the government so far has not
confirmed the report.
</P>
<P>
The rebel group said they beheaded two male teachers Wednesday
as the government had rejected their demands for the release of
two Abu Sayyaf members and others, including Ramzi Yousef who
masterminded the 1993 bombing of the World Trade Center in New
York.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf rebels took away about 50 people from two
schools in Basilan on March 20 as human shields after attacking a
government army post, but later they released some of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that if the radio report could be confirmed,
the army may start rescue operations soon. 
</P>
