<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Adopt Measures to Curb Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This was stated by spokesman of Pakistan's Ministry of Interior
Tasneem Noorani while addressing a press conference here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Noorani said that the objectives of the agenda is "to make
Pakistan a country where rule of law reigns supreme, every
Pakistani feels secure to lead a life in conformity with his
religious beliefs, culture, heritage and customs, where a
Pakistani from any group, sect or province respects the culture,
tradition and faith of the others and every foreign visitor feels
welcome and secure".
</P>
<P>
He said that eight points reforms agenda comprises de-
weaponisation, anti-smuggling, control of registration of Pakistan
and creating an authentic data base, control of aliens in Pakistan,
police reforms, jail reforms, computerization of immigrants
functions and sectarian issues.
</P>
<P>
The agenda came a week after the killing of 15 people in a
sectarian violence in northwestern Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Giving the implementation progress on the reforms agenda,
Noorani said that the government has banned display of weapons and
issuance of arms licenses.
</P>
<P>
To curb smuggling, the government has decided to revive Federal
Anti-Smuggling Coordination Council, which was disbanded in the
past, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said that security on the borders, railways, motorways have
been tightened to control smuggling which causing losses of
billion to the national coffer.
</P>
<P>
Noorani stated that the government has amended the foreigners
act and the punishment for illegal immigrants has been increased
from 5 to 10 years and their facilitators will also be held
responsible and undergo punishment of three years.
</P>
<P>
According to rough estimates, currently in Pakistan there are 2.
07 million Afghan refugees, 1.1 million Bengalis and some from
Burma, Iran, Iraq and other countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
