<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Increase Share in World Furniture  Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines will try to
increase its present 1 percent market share in the 38 billion U.S.
dollar world furniture market through improvements in the country'
s science and technology system.
</P>
<P>
During the launching of the Furniture and Handicraft Research
and Development (R&AMP;D) Program here Thursday, Department of Science
and Technology Secretary Filemon Uriarte said that as the
Philippine furniture export revenue amounts to around 300 million
dollars a year,there is still an immense room for growth.
</P>
<P>
Uriarte said the R&AMP;D program for the furniture and handicraft
industries may help boost their export prospects, particularly of
the wood furniture industry which is among the export market's
fastest-growing sectors.
</P>
<P>
"The program is all about dreaming and doing big things for the
industry because there is still so much ground that we can cover,
a very large slice of the export pie that we can grab hold of," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that the country's average furniture
export from 1994-1998 increased by 8 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, the furniture export revenue amounted to 322 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
A study found that the country's furniture and handicraft
export market potential is hindered by antiquated equipment,
insufficient supply of raw materials, comparable inferior products
and limited access to government support services.
</P>
<P>
Uriarte said the five-year R&AMP;D program is designed to remedy
these problems through research-based innovation system.  He said
that the Forest Products Research and Development Institute(FPRDI)
based in Los Banos, the Northern Philippines, will capitalize on
non-traditional wood and other forest materials to enhance
distinctive local design ingenuity.
</P>
<P>
It will also improve existing facilities and set up new
furniture training and testing centers in key points of the
country, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
