<HEADLINE> Federal Prosecutors Interview Clinton, Gore on Campaign Finance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Both U.S. President Bill
Clinton and Vice President Al Gore were interviewed by federal
prosecutors on alleged fund-raising abuses in 1996, White House
officials said.
</P>
<P>
"The president and the vice president cooperated fully with the
task force and voluntarily agreed to be interviewed this week," a
statement from White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's interview, which was under oath and lasted four hours,
took place in the White House Friday, with White House counsel
Beth Nolan in attendance, along with Clinton's private lawyers
David Kendall and Nicole Seligman, an official said.
</P>
<P>
A prosecutor and four Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)
agents conducted the interview, Clinton's third on campaign
finance. He was interviewed on November 11, 1997 and November 9,
1998, respectively.
</P>
<P>
A task force was established by Attorney General Janet Reno to
investigate allegations that illegal foreign and corporate
donations were made in the 1996 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
Gore was questioned for four hours Tuesday in the vice
presidential residence by Robert Conrad, head of the Justice
Department task force.
</P>
<P>
"I volunteered to cooperate fully, as I have from the beginning
of their investigation," Gore said at a press conference on his
campaign plane returning to Washington from Michigan.
</P>
<P>
He said he did not feel that the investigation will harm his
campaign for president.
</P>
<P>
Gore was questioned five times under oath involving various
investigations during the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic presidential nominee was plagued by a fund-
rasing event at a Buddhist temple in California in 1996. 
</P>
