<HEADLINE> Launch Countdown for Space Shuttle Atlantis Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Countdown has started Friday
afternoon for Monday's launch of Space Shuttle Atlantis, and seven
astronauts for the mission have arrived at Kennedy Space Center in
Florida making the last preparations.
</P>
<P>
The 10-day space flight, aimed at preparing the International
Space Station for the arrival of Russia's Zvezda Service Module,
is scheduled to start on Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Weather forecasters indicate a 70 percent chance for the launch.
</P>
<P>
As work to prepare Atlantis for launch continues, the
International Space Station continues to orbit the Earth as it
awaits the arrival of the seven-member crew, who will conduct
during the flight one spacewalk to perform maintenance on the
station and deliver logistics and supplies.
</P>
<P>
Crews normally train together for a year or more before launch,
but this crew was only finalized in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, workers in Kazakhstan have completed electrical
testing of the Zvezda Service Module.
</P>
<P>
The space shuttle features a new cockpit, technically called
the Multifunction Electronic Display Subsystem, which replaces
obsolete instruments and three monochrome computer screens with 11
full-color graphical displays.
</P>
<P>
The cockpit weighs less, uses less electricity, provides more
backup instruments and, most importantly, sets the stage for a
future "smart cockpit" now in development for the shuttle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
