IBRA controls over 200 trillion rupiah (26.1 billion U.S.
dollars) worth of nonperforming loans received from closed down
banks, recapitalized banks and nationalized banks.
</P>
<P>
The agency has a mandate to restructure and recover the loans
in a bid to help finance the government's bank restructuring costs,
estimated at more than 500 trillion rupiah.
</P>
<P>
IBRA has been criticized for its slow progress in the
restructuring of nonperforming loans, particularly large loans
owed by powerful businessmen.
</P>
<P>
IBRA is determined to take recalcitrant debtors to the
commercial court, but so far its earlier attempts have mostly
failed. 
