<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Set-up Special Anti-Corruption Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesia's Attorney General
Office (AGO) will set up an anti-corruption team to curb rampant
corruption in the country, local leading newspapers reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted Attorney General Marzuki Darusman as saying
that a former Supreme Court senior judge, Adi Andojo has been
appointed as the head of the team,
</P>
<P>
Marzuki said the team was established on the basis of a
government degree calling for the resolution of unsolved
corruption cases.
</P>
<P>
He said the establishment of the team was also part of the
country's effort to meet the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
demands that Jakarta be serious in handling corruption cases.
</P>
<P>
"The team will only deal with the investigation and prosecution
of corruption cases which are difficult to prove," Darusman added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Director of Corruption Affairs at the AGO Chairul
Imam was dismissed by Attorney General Marzuki Darusman on
Thursday "as a part of restructuring process within the AGO."
</P>
<P>
Marzuki defended his decision to dismiss Imam, saying that the
move formed part of an on-going internal process "to restructure
the AGO,boost professionalism, establish a good track record and
improve its performance."
</P>
<P>
But, the decision was criticized by some parliamentarians and
legal experts. They described the move as unsystematic and dubious
in nature.
</P>
<P>
However, some sources said the real reason for the dismissal
was that last week Imam issued a warrant for city arrest to
Indonesian former president Soeharto, rather than a house arrest
as preferred by the attorney general. 
</P>
