<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Bombing of Yugoslavia With Depleted Uranium Bombs Damages Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 21 (Xinhua) -- NATO dropped tens of thousands
of depleted uranium bombs on eight locations in Yugoslavia during
last year's airstrikes, causing widespread environmental damage, a
Yugoslav government report said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report, prepared by both Yugoslav and foreign experts, was
based on a yearlong study on the environmental effects of the NATO
airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
Large numbers of depleted uranium bombs banned by international
laws were dropped by NATO warplanes in southern part of Serbia and
Montenegro, which made the degree of radioactive contamination
there 1,000 times above the normal level, said Yugoslav Assistant
Defense Minister Slobodan Petkovich.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo was much more exposed since depleted uranium bombs were
dropped on 100 locations, Petkovich added.
</P>
<P>
Nada Sljapic, minister for science and development, said that
NATO deliberately targeted chemical facilities during last year's
airstrikes, which was "a flagrant chemical warfare against human
environment."
</P>
<P>
NATO admitted last month that its warplanes had dropped 31,000
depleted uranium bombs, but argued that they did not present a
significant hazard to health or environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
