<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul, Pyongyang Begin Preparatory Meeting for Inter-Korean Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANMUNJOM, South Korea, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Delegations from
Seoul and Pyongyang began their first preparatory meeting here
Saturday morning for an inter-Korean summit slated to open on June
12-14.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which began at 10: a.m. in the Peace House, just
south of the demilitarized zone bisecting the Korean Peninsula and
runs through Panmunjom, is under way now.
</P>
<P>
It is the first inter-Korean meeting in the border village
since July 1994 when preparatory talks for a summit between then
South Korean President Kim Young-sam and late Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) President Kim Il-sung broke off due to
the latter's sudden death.
</P>
<P>
"The preparatory talks will focus on the four-point proposals
President Kim Dae-jung made in the Berlin Declaration," said Yang
Young-shik, head of Seoul's delegation.
</P>
<P>
President Kim outlined four most pressing issues between the
two sides in Germany in early March this year -- inter-Korean
economic cooperation, the establishment of peace and mutual
prosperity on the Korean Peninsula, the reunions of separated
families and inter-Korean governmental-level talks.
</P>
<P>
Yang, who is vice unification minister, said his three-member
delegation will not stick to the reciprocity principle Seoul has
traditionally used.
</P>
<P>
"We will adopt a flexible approach in dealing with the North
and will not seek any immediate reward in providing economic
assistance," said the vice minister who once met DPRK officials in
Beijing, China.
</P>
<P>
"As the preliminary talks will pave the way for a summit aimed
at laying the foundation for South-North reconciliation and
cooperation, we will not make any judgment as to who is right or
wrong, but to sound out each other's positions," Yang, who has
worked in the Unification Ministry for 28 years.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides must become winners from the talks," added the vice
minister.
</P>
<P>
In a crucial breakthrough after a half-century of division,
Seoul and Pyongyang reached an agreement in Beijing on April 8,
under which, President Kim will travel to Pyongyang for a summit
with DPRK leader Kim Jong-il on June 12-14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
