<HEADLINE> Karpov Aims at Winning JAPFA Classic Chess Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Chess legend and former world
champion Grand Master (GM) Anatoly Karpov aims at winning the 56,
500 U.S. dollars JAPFA Classic International Chess Tournament in
Bali, Indonesia, from April 22 to May 2.
</P>
<P>
Karpov, whose ELO rating is 2696, said after arriving at the
Bali international airport on Friday that he expected tough games
with other competitors, who have ELO ratings only slightly
different from his.
</P>
<P>
He said the winner will certainly be a player who is in top
form.
</P>
<P>
"As usual, I want to win. But firstly, it all depends on our
form, preparation and the playing situation. The tournament is
quite tough and some players are good, including Khalifman. I'm
expecting an interesting game," he was quoted by the Jakarta Post
Saturday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Karpov was referring to fellow countryman GM Alexander
Khalifman (2656) who won the 1999 FIDE world championship in Las
Vegas, U.S. Karpov was the world champion in 1975, 1985, 1993 and
1999.
</P>
<P>
Karpov arrived in Bali with advisor Mikhail Podgaets, who has
worked for him for about two decades.
</P>
<P>
Other competitors are GM Yasser Seirawan (United States, 2647),
GM Jan Timman (Netherlands, 2655), women's chess player GM Judit
Polgar (Hungary, 2658), GM Jaan Ehlvest (Estonia, 2622), GM
Gilberto Milos Jr. (Brazil, 2586), International Master Zaw Win
Lay (Myanmar, 2633) and another host player GM Ruben Gunawan (2510)
. 
</P>
