<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dianchi Lake Suffers Severe Algae Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Blue-green algae, which has
threatened Dianchi Lake, the biggest of the kind in southwest
China's Yunnan Province, for three decades, will soon be out of
control again, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, the provincial government has spent
more than three billion yuan (361 million U.S. dollars) in the
past decade trying to bring the algae under control.
</P>
<P>
However, Chen Xunru, deputy governor of Yunnan, admitted that
the best solution to the problem is still unclear.
</P>
<P>
Blue-green algae, a kind of water plant, grows easily in
polluted water with a high concentration of nitrogen and
phosphorous and with a temperature around 18 degrees Celsius.
</P>
<P>
Too much blue-green algae will remove oxygen from the water
killing fish and other aquatic life, and can turn Dianchi into a "
dead" lake.
</P>
<P>
Blue-green algae has been threatening Dianchi Lake since 1970s.
Last year, blue-green algae covered 20 km of the lake, accounting
for one fifteenth of the lake's total area.
</P>
<P>
Four sewage treatment plants were built near the lake since
1993. They able to treat 365,000 tons of waster water each day.
</P>
<P>
A government-led campaign last year forced 249 of the 253
factories along the lake to stop dumping their industrial sewage
into the lake.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the government also spent 250 million yuan (30
million U.S. dollars) to dredge 4.2 million cu m of mud.
</P>
<P>
But the efforts fell short. The network to collect sewage is
incomplete and more than 80 percent of domestic sewage with
fertilizers and pesticides still flow into the lake through 16
rivers, said experts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Stresses Protection of Earth Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- China marked the 30th World Earth
Day today with a number of activities in downtown areas of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
China is one of the countries most threatened by geological
disasters, Tian Fengshan, minister of land and resources, said in
the Chinese capital today, stressing that more should be done to
protect the geological environment.
</P>
<P>
China should further improve the laws and regulations in this
regard, improve scientific research on forecasting geological
disasters, and enhance the ability to prevent geological disasters
and minimize the country's losses.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China annually suffers from about 30
varieties of geological disasters including landslides, mud-rock
flows, avalanches, earthquakes, desertification, water and soil
erosion, and more than 50 percent of them are the result of human
activities.
</P>
<P>
These disasters cause direct economic losses of about 30
billion yuan (3.6 billion U.S. dollars) each year.
</P>
<P>
China has issued regulations on protection of geological relics,
and prevention and control of geological disasters. A geological
environmental monitoring network has been nearly completed in the
country.
</P>
<P>
During the past two years, the Ministry of Land and Resources
organized experts to study the geological environment, and 52
large-scale geological disasters were successfully forecast.
</P>
<P>
World Earth Day originated in the United States 30 years ago,
aiming to raise global awareness of environmental issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Science News: Weekly Highlights (2)  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese Scientists Boast Spacecraft Welding Techniques
</P>
<P>
China has successfully applied advanced welding techniques to
the building of its first outerspace aircraft, the "Shenzhou" that
was launched last November.
</P>
<P>
The techniques, combination welding and deformation control,
were applied to the return cabin of the experimental spacecraft,
which touched down without any damage, fully indicating that China
's spacecraft welding technique is mature and has reached the
world advanced level.
</P>
<P>
International Conference on Life Science Opens in Beijing
</P>
<P>
The International Conference on Life Science and Clinical
Medicine 2000, sponsored by the Chinese Academy of Engineering,
opened in Beijing Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,200 Chinese experts and medical workers and more
than 80 foreign scholars attended the conference which is co-
hosted by the China Science and Technology Association and 11
other organizations.
</P>
<P>
China Builds Ecological Demonstration Zones
</P>
<P>
China, worrying about a worsening environment, will take
effective measures to turn 140 of its 2,000 counties and
prefectures into ecological demonstration zones over the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
These counties and prefectures are to meet the economic, social,
and environmental requirements of China's sustainable development
strategy in 2005.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Websites Join Hands to Protect Tibetan Antelopes
</P>
<P>
Several well-known Chinese websites entered a web alliance
Monday to protect the Tibetan antelopes from extinction.
</P>
<P>
The websites include Chinaren.com and east.cn.net, whose fund-
raising and international cooperation activities are supported by
university students in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetan antelope, one of the top priorities on China's
protected species list, is an endangered species. The animals live
in the grassland in and around Qinghai, the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region and Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Asteroid Named after Yangzhou City
</P>
<P>
An asteroid 220 million kilometers away from the Earth was
named "Yangzhou" for a city along the Yangtze River, an
international center of asteroid studies announced.
</P>
<P>
The asteroid, numbered 3729 in the international series, was
discovered in November 1983 by astronomers in the Zijinshan
Astronomical Observatory in Nanjing, the provincial capital of
Jiangsu in east China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
