<HEADLINE> Chinese Science News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are highlights of
major science stories released by Xinhua this week:
</P>
<P>
Biologic Method Used to Kill Cotton Aphid
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists have developed a biologic method to prevent
and kill cotton aphid so as to guarantee cotton production and
promote the development of animal husbandry.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the Ecological and Geological Research
Institute of Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, affiliated to the
China Academy of Sciences, built belts of clover around the cotton
fields for the purpose to kill aphids.
</P>
<P>
Students Studying Overseas to Attend Beijing High-Tech Week
</P>
<P>
Some 40 students studying overseas will attend the Third
Beijing International High-Tech Week slated for May 8-12 this year.
</P>
<P>
Majority of these students have already received doctoral
degree and are now at important positions of various high-tech
companies in such countries as the U.S., Britain, Canada and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
China to Use Nuclear Power in Central Heating System
</P>
<P>
China is planning to provide heating service using nuclear
power in the city of Shenyang in northeast China's Liaoning
Province. And if successful, the major industrial base will
probably become the first city in the world to apply nuclear in
such a field.
</P>
<P>
The project, which has just been approved by the State Planning
Development Commission, will need 1.4 billion yuan (about 168
million U.S. dollars) for the construction of two low-temperature
nuclear reactors. Major funding will come from the local sources.
</P>
<P>
China to Set Up "Photoelectron Valley" in Northeast
</P>
<P>
Plans are underway to establish the Changchun Photoelectronic
Industrial Park, or the "Photoelectron Valley of China," in the
city of Changchun in northeast China's Jilin Province.
</P>
<P>
The project, under the auspices of the Changchun Institute of
Optics and Fine Mechanics and Physics under the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, and the Changchun Economic Development Zone, will be
crucial for the development of the country's photoelectron
industry and national defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
