<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Legal News Items This Week in China (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China Drafts Law on Defense Education
</P>
<P>
China is drafting the law on national defense education to
create greater public awareness about the nature and importance of
national defense.
</P>
<P>
A number of forums have been held in northeastern, eastern and
southwestern areas to solicit suggestions from local officials,
experts and representatives from different circles.
</P>
<P>
A draft is expected to be completed within this year and will
be submitted to the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress, the top legislature, for further review.
</P>
<P>
Sex Crimes Decrease in Beijing
</P>
<P>
The number of sex crimes has declined over the past 20 years in
Beijing, according to statistics from local courts.
</P>
<P>
Although crime in general is increasing, fewer than three
percent of the criminal cases are sex related, seven percent lower
than in the early '80s.
</P>
<P>
The improvement was partially due to harsh crackdowns by the
police. A spokesman for the Beijing Public Security Bureau said
Tuesday that the police closed down three unlicensed night clubs
on April 7, fining 5,000 yuan and arresting 53 female escorts.
</P>
<P>
Two days later, police searched three other entertainment
venues and found 44 drug traffickers, confiscating 40 pills and 11.
2 grams of ice.
</P>
<P>
Kidnapping Ring Busted
</P>
<P>
A kidnapping ring which abducted 84 women and children and
forced them to provide sexual services has been destroyed, the
Ministry of Public Security confirmed earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
A police investigation revealed that since 1997, Wang Heqiao, a
female farmer in Zunyi County, southwest China's Guizhou Province,
has collaborated with a dozen of her family members in abducting
84 women in her county.
</P>
<P>
Farmer Jailed for Selling Golden Monkey Skin
</P>
<P>
A farmer in northwest China's Shaanxi Province is now serving a
three-year jail term for illegally selling the skin of a state-
protected golden monkey.
</P>
<P>
Kang Xiangjun, a farmer in Taibai County, was convicted earlier
this year by a local court of skinning a golden monkey he found in
a hill near his home last year and attempting to sell.
</P>
<P>
In another development of environmental protection, more than 2,
000 illegally captured wild birds were released in north China's
Tianjin Municipality earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
As the largest port city in north China, Tianjin is an
important habitat for many Asian migrant birds. Qilihai, a nature
reserve there, is a resting place for more than 100 kinds of birds,
including a dozen of rare birds.
</P>
<P>
Crackdown on Smuggling Successful in Guangxi
</P>
<P>
The Nanning Customs in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region has cracked 167 smuggling cases and confiscated 13 million
yuan worth of goods in the first quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
The number of smuggling cases customs dealt with decreased by
one percent while money from the smuggled goods decreased 35
percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, police in Nanning handled 88 smuggling cases,
confiscated 75 million yuan worth of goods, seized dozens of
smugglers' boats and trucks, and arrested 48 smugglers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Health News in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are highlights of
major news on health care and medical research in China over the
past week:
</P>
<P>
Biggest Health Threats in China
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by China's Ministry of Health show that
cancer and respiratory illness remain the biggest health threats
to the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
About 140 out of every 100,000 Chinese urbanities died of
cancer and some 133 out of every 100,000 rural people died of
respiratory illnesses last year, making these the major causes of
death in the country.
</P>
<P>
Control over Medicine Quality Tightened
</P>
<P>
A sample survey of 8,501 kinds of medicine revealed that 754
failed to meet state standards. Compared with 2.7 percent
substandard drug products from pharmaceutical plants, about 12
percent of the drugs available in drug stores or used in hospitals
were of poor quality.
</P>
<P>
State Drug Administration, which oversees the country's
pharmaceutical industry, said on Monday that it will take
effective measures to strengthen supervision over the quality of
medicine and stem fake products from flowing into the market.
</P>
<P>
More Young Chinese Susceptible to Cancer
</P>
<P>
Specialists with the Chinese Academy of Medical Science advised
the Chinese people to undergo cancer check-ups before the age of
30 because more and more young people are becoming susceptible to
the killer disease.
</P>
<P>
The high-risk age group for malignant tumors such as the
stomach cancer and esophagus is between 35 and 40, about 10 years
younger than previously.
</P>
<P>
Official Emphasizes on Medical Ethics
</P>
<P>
A Chinese health official urged the circle to pay attention to
ethical problems triggered by rapid progress in medical technology.
</P>
<P>
Although high technology has led to more advanced treatment,
many problems also appear to be unavoidable, such as rocketing
medical expenses, regional imbalance in health-care resources, and
euthanasia, said Zhu Zonghan, director of the Beijing Municipal
Bureau of Health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Health News in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Revenue of Pharmaceutical Sector Up
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that the sales revenue of China's
pharmaceutical industry grew 13.7 percent to reach 116.6 billion
yuan in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The profits of pharmaceutical plants across the country totaled
168 million yuan, 21 percent more than that a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
China Close to Finishing HGP Task
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists announced Monday they are close to finishing
their quota to sequence chromosome 3, about 30 million base-pairs
of the human chromosomes, which accounts for one percent of human
genomes to be deciphered.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists joined last September a nine-year old
international project aimed at deciphering human genomes by 2003,
which determine the health and longevity of human beings.
</P>
<P>
New Gamma Ray Medical Facility Developed
</P>
<P>
A new medical facility using Gamma rays to treat tumors, called
the dimensional and directional Gamma ray treatment system, has
been developed in China.
</P>
<P>
Compared with traditional medical facilities using Gamma rays
to treat brain tumors, this new facility can be used to treat
tumors anywhere in the body.
</P>
<P>
Fewer Hospitals, More Doctors in China
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by China's Ministry of Health show a drop
in the number of medical institutes and a slow growth in the ranks
of medical personnel.
</P>
<P>
China had a total of 311,000 hospitals, clinics, disease
prevention agencies, health care centers, research institutes, and
medical schools and colleges by the end of 1999, compared with 314,
100 in 1998. Some 5.57 million people worked in these institutions,
a rise of about 35,000 over 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Health News in China (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Shandong to Develop Traditional Medicine
</P>
<P>
A center combining research and development, production and
trading of traditional Chinese medicine (TCM) is scheduled to be
built in three to five years in east China's Shandong Province,
which has set the goal of having the TCM industry account for at
least five percent of the province's future gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to establish six state-level bases for
growing herbs used in TCM, and to develop a great variety of TCM
while setting up outlets for their sale.
</P>
<P>
Int'l Medical Equipment Exhibition in Beijing
</P>
<P>
The 9th China International Medical Equipment and Facilities
Exhibition opened in Beijing on Wednesday, with some 2,000
advanced products on display.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 companies from 17 countries, including China,
Austria, Finland, the United States and Japan, displayed their
products for diagnosis, monitoring, treatment, rehabilitation, and
health promotion at the China International Exhibition Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, April 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno Friday refused
to set a timetable for reuniting the six-year-old Cuban shipwreck
survivor Elian Gonzalez after meeting with the boy's father.
</P>
<P>
After the 15-minute meeting at the Justice Department with Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, Reno said in a short statement that she told him
that "I could not commit to a particular course of action or
timetable."
</P>
<P>
"I was deeply moved by Mr. Gonzalez' evident love for his son...
I assured him I would continue working toward the goal of
reuniting him with his child," Reno said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
Reno said the father expressed great concern for and requested
a quick reunion with the boy, who has been here for nearly five
months since he survived in the Atlantic sea off Florida. The boy
's mother and 10 others were all drowned. (US-Cuba-Boy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HARARE -- The African countries involved in the civil conflict
in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) Friday agreed to
create an atmosphere of trust and commitment among themselves so
that the Lusaka peace agreement which was signed last year could
hold.
</P>
<P>
Briefing reporters after a one-day summit on the DRC conflict
held in Zimbabwe's prime resort town of Victoria Falls, Mozambican
President Joaquin Chissano who chaired the meeting said all the
four external forces that were represented agreed to meet
regularly to discuss the cease-fire issue.
</P>
<P>
The summit was also attended by South African President Thabo
Mbeki, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, Namibian President Sam
Nujoma, Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and Rwandan Foreign
Minister Andrei Bumaya.
</P>
<P>
The summit was meant to find ways of reducing the escalating
hostilities in the DRC and bringing trust and goodwill among the
six countries involved in the conflict. (Zimbabwe-Congo-Democracy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi Friday evening
gave current Treasury Minister Giuliano Amato the mandate to form
new government.
</P>
<P>
The ruling center-left coalition on Friday morning announced to
propose 61-year-old Amato as the premier-designate to replace the
outgoing government leader Massimo D'Alema, who resigned on
Wednesday for losing the regional election last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
If Amato does pass a confidence vote in both houses, he has
made it plain that he wants to lead the alliance not only through
next month's electoral reform, but into the next general election,
scheduled for next spring. (Italy-Government) 
</P>
</TEXT>
