<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Not to Cede Rights or Territory: Syrian Front </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Syria would not cede any of its
rights or give up any inch of its territory, said the central
leadership of Syria's National Progressive National Front.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the united front of the ruling Baath Arab Socialist
Party and other five major political parties met here Saturday
night. They listened to a report by Foreign Minister Faruk Shareh
on the latest developments of the peace process on the Syrian
track.
</P>
<P>
The leaders reiterated that a just and fair peace would be
conducive to the overall regional security and stability, according
to Syria's official news agency.
</P>
<P>
On the talks with Israel, the leaders said Israeli government
was not serious in achieving peace in the Middle East based on
international legitimacy and principles and a full Israeli
withdrawal to June 1967 borders.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that "Syria categorically rejects any form of
ceding its rights or giving up any inch of its territory."
</P>
<P>
Syrian-Israeli peace talks were resumed in Washington in
December after a break of nearly four years, but they hit a snag
again after two fruitless rounds in January.
</P>
<P>
The two sides mainly disagreed over where their borderline
should be drawn. Syria demands a full Israeli withdrawal from the
Golan Heights it captured in the 1967 Middle East, while Israel
refuses to make an advance commitment.
</P>
<P>
On Israel's planned pullback from south Lebanon, the central
leadership of the Syrian front considered the Israeli move as a
victory for the Lebanese resistance which upholds Syria's stand, it
was reported.
</P>
<P>
Israel has decided to pull out its troops from the self-styled
security zone in south Lebanon, carved out in 1985 after two
invasions, by June, even in the absence of a peace agreement with
Lebanon and its main power broker Syria.
</P>
<P>
The leadership of the front vowed to continue working hard to
promote Arab solidarity as "an insurmountable wall against all
risks and challenges." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
