<HEADLINE> Iran Must Find Out Causes of Insecurity: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Interior Minister Seyed
Abdolvahed Mousavi Lari said here on Saturday that Iran must find
out the root causes of insecurity which is worrying the supreme
leader.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry and all provincial governments should try
to identify the root causes of the insecurity in the society and
adopt effective measures to strengthen unity and national security,
Lari told a meeting of governor-generals of all the 28 provinces.
</P>
<P>
Iran's supreme leader Seyyed Ali Khamenei recently expressed his
strong opposition to U.S.-style reforms, gave warnings to reformist
newspapers and called for "legal violence" to deal with activities
threatening the Islamic system.
</P>
<P>
Elaborating on the remarks of the leader, Lari said that
security in every society depends on the behaviors and acts of the
different groups of the society, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the incidents that occurred since moderate
President Mohammed Khatami came to power in 1997, the minister said
during the electoral campaign for the presidential elections some
individuals were spreading the rumors that if Khatami became
president, insecurity would dominate the country.
</P>
<P>
He further said that the recent social commotion has been
masterminded by those who were promoting the theory of insecurity
during the presidential elections which resulted in a landslide
victory for President Khatami.
</P>
<P>
The minister mentioned the serial killings of moderate
intellectuals and writers last year, saying the crimes were
committed by those who intended to show that the government was
unable to establish security in the country.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the sixth parliamentary election in February which
ended in the overwhelming victory for reformers, Lari said the
election has been held in a sounder atmosphere compared to the last
round of the legislative polls.
</P>
<P>
However, Lari said, "I do not know why the results of some
constituencies have been invalidated by the Guardian Council (GC)."
</P>
<P>
As a watchdog of the election, the conservative-dominated GC has
cancelled the election results in a number of constituencies,
resulting in a series of protests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
