<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia, Global Oil Companies Discuss Saudi Energy Development Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia on Saturday
resumed talks with three international oil companies who are
seeking a share in the Saudi energy development pie.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi ministerial committee in charge of the talks held
separate meetings with the board chairmen of the American oil
giants Texaco, Enron and Occidental in the Saudi city of Jeddah.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Saudi committee had already held meetings with
other three oil majors, namely Royal Dutch/Shell, Chevron and the
Phillips Petroleum Company.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Crown Prince invited international oil companies to invest
in the Gulf oil kingdom's energy sector in 1998.
</P>
<P>
A total of 12 international oil companies responded and
submitted investment offers to the Saudi government.
</P>
<P>
Since last Monday, chiefs of the companies have been arriving in
Saudi Arabia to hear feedbacks about their investment proposals.
</P>
<P>
While experts estimate these companies could invest around 30
billion U.S. dollars, Riyadh is hoping to attract up to 100 billion
dollars in its upstream gas sector and downstream oil sector.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the world's largest oil producer with gas reserves
of 6 trillion cubic meters and 261 billion barrels of proven oil
reserves, has stated that its upstream oil sector will remain off
limits to foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Foreign Minister Saud Al-Faisal, who heads the ministerial
committee, has said that the "objective of the negotiations is not
seeking technology for the development of oil, but for investment
in gas and downstream oil."
</P>
<P>
Al-Faisal said the oil industry is being run at the highest
level of professionalism by using Saudi staff.
</P>
<P>
The management of oil industry in the Kingdom has "reached a
level of efficiency that makes it match any international
standard," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
