<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peruvian Banks Sell 1.547 Bln Dlrs to Private Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian banks have sold 1.547
billion dollars to private companies this year, the "Gestion"
newspaper, specialized in economic issues, said Saturday .
</P>
<P>
The financial report says in reference to cash exchange
operations that so far banking institutions have sold 4.345
billion dollars and bought 5.442 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
These transactions have been made in a context in which the
national currency has undergone a 0.14 percent revaluation or
appreciation when the average interbank dollar diminished from 3,
486 to 3,481 soles, the national currency.
</P>
<P>
Forward dollar purchase and sale operations have been bigger in
the last weeks, taking into account the political events and the
fear of new rises in the U.S. rates of interest, which makes more
costly foreign financing, according to financial analysts.
</P>
<P>
However, they explain that this has not been so, because the
lesser availability of soles has forced the banks to acquire more
national currency and sell it at future.
</P>
<P>
The increase of dollars sales to Peruvian firms shows that
these private entities are trying to protect themselves from an
eventual future increase in the exchange rate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
