<DOCNO> XIE20000422.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (EDS: with new lead, more details) Elian Reunited With Father, Relatives Arrives in Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The U.S. federal government seized the six-year-old Cuban boy
from the home of his Miami relatives in a predawn raid, ending a
five-month standoff between the government and Elian's Miami
relatives.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno both
indicated that the authorities used force to remove Elian from his
relatives in Miami after they refused to surrender the boy
voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
Despite the happy reunion of the father and son, some U.S.
politicians were critical of the administration's handling of the
case.
</P>
<P>
"The chilling picture of a little boy being removed from his
home at gunpoint defies the values of America and is not an image
a freedom-loving nation wants to show the world," Republican
presidential candidate George W. Bush said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Ours is a nation of laws, not guns. Custody disputes are
resolved in the calm of a courtroom, not in the terror of middle
of the night raids," Bush said.
</P>
<P>
An Associated Press photo taken when the raid took place showed
that the a federal agent pointed a gun at Elian.
</P>
<P>
Reno told reporters that "if you look carefully" at the picture,
"it shows that the gun was pointed to the side, and that the
finger was not on the trigger."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Services (INS) agents
stormed the home of his Miami relatives in Little Havana at 5:15 a.
m, local time Saturday, firing pepper spray into an angry crowd
and took away the boy for the reunion with his father.
</P>
<P>
Elian was brought out of the home by a woman agent, put into a
van and whisked away. By six o'clock, the boy has been put on an
airplane heading to Washington.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. official said the boy was accompanied by the female
immigration agent who picked him up from the home, a surgeon and
the immigration agent who led the raid. He was given a play kit
including toys, a toy plane, a map and a watch.
</P>
<P>
Elian's father, who arrived in Washington on April 4, has been
waiting in Washington for about two weeks to take custody of his
son.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton defended the forceful seizure of
Elian Gonzalez, saying that the right thing has been done for the
six-year-old Cuban boy.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he totally supports the attorney general's
decision to send federal agents in to take the boy from his
Florida relatives.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters at the White House that Reno had gone to
great lengths to convince the Florida relatives to voluntarily
give up the boy, and was left with no alternative other than to
use force. The law has been upheld and the right thing has been
done, he added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was kept informed throughout the night of the progress
of the negotiations between the Justice Department and Gonzalez's
relatives, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
After being told by his chief of staff John Podesta that all-
night negotiations to resolve the custody dispute failed, Clinton
said that he was disappointed and gave the green light to seize
the boy from the Miami home of his great uncle Lazaro Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
Reno told a press conference that the government tried every
way it could to get the family of the Miami relatives to surrender
the boy before taking the action, but the negotiations failed and
the family refused to turn over the boy.
</P>
<P>
Reno said the paramount concern for the morning's raid was the
safety of the child.
</P>
<P>
She said eight federal agents were in the house and one female
agent picked up Elian. She spoke with him in Spanish. The whole
process lasted for three minutes.
</P>
<P>
Reno said that the Justice Department will abide by an appeals
court rule that the boy will remain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Elian's father expressed his gratitude to the U.S. authorities.
"We are grateful to the attorney general and the Department of
Justice for upholding the law with utmost concern for the safety
and well-being of Elian Gonzalez," the father's attorney, Greg
Craig, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The attorney general was tireless. She was insistent that we
continue our effort to achieve a peaceful and voluntary transfer
of custody."
</P>
<P>
"We too are sad that force was required, but to the very end
Lazaro Gonzalez placed road blocks in the path of an orderly
transfer of custody. He gave the attorney general no alternative."
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta
issued an order that keeps Elian in the United States pending an
appeal for an asylum filed by the relatives in Miami for the boy.
</P>
<P>
Elian was rescued on November 25 near a shipwreck in the
Atlantic sea off Florida after his mother and 10 others drowned
when their boat capsized.
</P>
<P>
Elian has been living in the home of his great-uncle Lazaro
Gonzalez since then. U.S. authorities spent weeks trying to
arrange a peaceful transfer of Elian from the relatives to his
father.
</P>
<P>
Cuban Americans demonstrated for weeks outside the home to
block the transfer.
</P>
<P>
Early in the year, the INS ruled that the boy belongs to his
father and should be returned to Cuba. However, the Miami
relatives insist the boy should stay with them in the United
States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
