<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Approves Elian's Return to His Father </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Cuban government Saturday
approved "the much expected and emotional" encounter of boy Elian
Gonzalez with his father in Washington, according to an official
report repeatedly broadcast by the local radio and television.
</P>
<P>
The media have maintained the people of the island abreast
through communiques of the events that started past five on
Saturday's morning, when U.S. federal agents entered the house in
Miami where Elian was retained.
</P>
<P>
The agents took Elian and immediately sent him to the Andrews
air base to join his father, who, according to the photographs
transmitted at midday, were very happy with their reencounter.
</P>
<P>
Communique No. 3 says that "the delivery of the boy to his
father means a favorable turn toward a just, honorable and right
solution to the problem."
</P>
<P>
The meeting occurred at the air base at 09:43 local time, five
months and two days after November 20, 1999, when they were
separated without the knowledge of his father.
</P>
<P>
The communique says that Elian, his father Juan Miguel and his
wife, and the couple's youngest son will remain Saturday for some
hours at the base, while Juan Miguel and his lawyer analyze the
subsequent steps related to their presence in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Atlanta Court of Appeals decided that they cannot return
immediately to Cuba before the end of a judicial process started
after a demand of political asylum for Elian filed by his Miami
far-removed relatives.
</P>
<P>
It is foreseen that a court will be in session on May 11 to
decide on the case, while Attorney General Janet Reno insists that
only the father has the legal capacity to speak for Elian.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban authorities have stated since their first communique,
broadcast here after six in the morning, "the need and high
convenience" of not staging public demonstrations in the island "
which could influence negatively the future evolution of the
situation."
</P>
<P>
The people have responded with discipline to this call, but
happiness is seen everywhere, in every house where the radio and
television is heard and seen and in the positive comments among
the families.
</P>
<P>
The news of Elian and Juan Miguel's reencounter was awaited
with anxiety by the Cubans in the island, who have not ceased to
reclaim since December 5, with marches, open forums, and round
tables the repatriation of the boy.
</P>
<P>
An open forum has been convoked Saturday afternoon in Jaguey
Grande municipality in the western province of Matanzas, where
Cardenas, Elian's hometown, is located.
</P>
<P>
The official report says that "the need to fight for Elian has
not ended, but the delivery of the child to his father means a
favorable turn toward the just, honorable, and correct solution to
the problem."
</P>
<P>
The federal operation to take Elian and deliver him to his
father occurred 48 hours after Juan Miguel called on the U.S.
people to support him in his claim for his six-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
Elian survived the wreckage of a raft with 14 illegal emigrants,
a tragedy in which his mother and other 10 persons drowned, so the
U.S. migratory authorities gave temporary custody to a grand-uncle
in Miami.
</P>
<P>
The Miami relatives had refused since then to surrender the
minor, despite the reiterated demands of Juan Miguel, who had the
support of his government from the first moment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
