<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian President Accepts Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso said Saturday in his speech commemorating the 500
anniversary of the discovery of the country that Indians, blacks
and landless peasants have a reason to demonstrate.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso said during a breakfast with his Portuguese counterpart,
Jorge Sampaio, in Porto Seguro that the celebration of a
historical date does not mean to idealize the past.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese navigator Pedro Alvares Cabral arrived in Brazil on
April 22, 1500.
</P>
<P>
President Cardoso admitted that the society of the country is
unjust for millions of Indians, blacks and landless workers, left
out of the benefits of development. He said that democracy is the
main instrument to fight that social exclusion.
</P>
<P>
In Brazil, a country with over 8.5 million square kilometers of
soil, 90 percent of the land is in the hands of 20 percent of the
people, while the poorest 40 percent own just 1 percent. The
democracy has ahead a long process of institutional perfecting to
guarantee levels of transparency in public life, which are
demanded by an increasingly best informed society, he said.
</P>
<P>
Brazil will continue struggling against corruption and impunity
that threaten democratic coexistence, reform the transformation of
the aged institutions, and preserve stability and economic growth,
said the president.
</P>
<P>
Some 140 Indian demonstrators, members of the Landless Movement
(MST) and of other groups were detained Saturday morning when they
fought police in Coroa Vermelha near the Porto Seguro municipality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
